{[%evp 0,23,26,26,24,-3,12,4,44,47,48,53,32,-8,28,38,21,0,27,-12,-32,-21,-22,-25,-14,-70]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 {This is the starting position of the Marshall Gambit, Main Line. White gives up the center in exchange for the bishop pair and quicker development.} Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 {[%csl Gb4,Ge2]} Na6 9. Bd6 Qxg2 {All sidelines are analyzed in the next chapter.} 10. Bf3 $5 {At the end of 2023, Abdusattorov brought this move back to popularity. We want to quickly play Ne2–Ng3–Ne4 and exploit the open g-file. What I really like about this line is how much Black needs to be deeply prepared with an engine to maintain equality.} (10. Qd2 {is the main move for White, but it doesn't offer any real fight for an advantage. In fact, Black can equalize with precise moves, leading to a balanced position} Nf6 11. Bf3 Qg6 12. O-O-O e5 $1 13. Bxe5 Be6 14. Ne2 Qf5 15. Bf4 Qc5 16. Nc3 (16. b3 Qa3+ 17. Kb1 Bf5+ 18. Ka1 O-O $1 19. Bd6 Nc5 20. Qe3 Nfd7 21. Bxf8 Nxf8 $44 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gf8e6] Citak,S (2319)-Subelj,J (2508) Ustron POL 2023}) 16... Qxc4 17. Be2 Qb4 18. Bxa6 bxa6 19. Bd6 Qb7 20. Bc5 Nd5 21. Ne4 O-O-O 22. Nd6+ Rxd6 23. Bxd6 Rd8 24. Ba3 Bg4 25. Rde1 Bf5 $11 {Eventually, Yoo won the game, but in my opinion, Black has enough compensation and a stable position. Yoo,C (2548)-Burke,J (2579) Saint Louis 2022}) 10... Qg5 (10... Qg6 11. Ne2 Ne7 $146 (11... Nf6 {The most played move, but it is a mistake!} 12. Rg1 $1 Qf5 13. Nd4 Qa5+ 14. b4 Nxb4 15. Kf1 e5 {Greifenberg,D (2147)-Schmider,N (2341) Muenster GER 2021} 16. Qe1 Bh3+ 17. Bg2 Bxg2+ 18. Rxg2 O-O-O 19. Bxb4 $16) (11... Nh6 $5 12. Qd2 (12. Rg1 $5 {is another way of playing this position} Qf6 13. Nc3 Nf5 14. Ne4 Qxb2 15. Rb1 Qd4 16. Qe2 Bd7 17. c5 {The result is a complex position where both outcomes are possible.}) 12... Bd7 13. O-O-O (13. Rd1 $1 e5 14. Rg1 Qe6 15. Bxe5 Nf5 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. Rxg7 O-O-O $13) 13... e5 {[%cal Gg6e6]} (13... O-O-O 14. Be7 $16) 14. Rhg1 Qe6 15. Bxe5 Nf5 16. Bg4 O-O-O 17. Bxg7 Rhg8 18. b3 $13 {[%cal Gg7c3,Gd2f4] White has a very pleasant position thanks to his extra space and more harmonious pieces.}) 12. Qd2 Qf6 (12... Nf5 13. O-O-O $1 Qh6 (13... Nxd6 14. Bxc6+ $3 {Beautiful way to end the game!} bxc6 15. Qxd6 $18 {[%cal Gd6d8,Gd6c6]}) 14. Bf4 Qh4 15. Bg4 $1 {[%cal Rh4g4,Rd2d8]} O-O 16. Rhg1 g6 17. Rg2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf4g5]} Qf6 18. Bg5 Qe5 19. Bxf5 $1 (19. f3 $5 $14 {/}) 19... exf5 (19... Qxf5 $2 20. Be7 Re8 21. Ng3 $18 {[%cal Gg3e4,Gd2h6]}) 20. Nf4 Nc5 21. f3 Ne6 22. Nh5 $16 {and it would be difficult for Black to survive this!}) 13. O-O-O $1 Qxf3 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Qd6+ Kf6 16. Ng3 g5 $1 {[%cal Gf3f4]} 17. Kb1 Kg6 18. h4 f6 19. hxg5 fxg5 20. Rde1 $1 h5 21. Rhg1 g4 22. Re5 {[%csl Ra6,Ra8,Rc8,Rg6][%cal Gg3e4,Gg1d1] Good luck to Black in a practical game, trying to survive this dangerous position.}) 11. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2g3,Gg3e4]} Ne7 (11... Nh6 $5 {[%cal Gh6f5]} 12. Ng3 e5 (12... Nf5 {transpose to 11...Ne7}) 13. b4 $1 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gb4b5]} Nf5 14. b5 $1 Nb8 15. Ne4 Qd8 16. O-O {[%csl Re8]} Be6 17. Re1 Nd7 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. Ba3 $14 {[%csl Re8] /}) 12. Ng3 $1 {[%cal Gh2h4]} e5 (12... Nf5 13. Nxf5 Qxf5 $1 {is the right move to fight for equality!} (13... exf5 $2 {Black's position collapses quickly after this move. Tari didn’t have too many problems converting the position to a win.} 14. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Ra8,Rc8,Gd6,Gf3][%cal Ge1f1,Ga1e1,Re8g8]} Nb8 15. Kf1 {[%cal Ga1e1]} Qh6 16. c5 {[%cal Ga1e1]} b5 17. cxb6 axb6 18. Re1+ Be6 19. Qxb6 Qh3+ 20. Ke2 Nd7 21. Qxc6 Rb8 22. b4 $18 {Tari,A (2635)-Maurizzi,M (2597) Djerba 2024}) 14. Qe2 Bd7 (14... e5 15. Rg1 Be6 16. Rxg7 O-O-O 17. Bg4 Qf6 18. Bxe5 Qe7 19. Bxe6+ Qxe6 20. Bc3 Qf5 $1 (20... Rhg8 21. Qxe6+ fxe6 22. Ke2 Rxg7 23. Bxg7 $14 {[%csl Ya6,Gg7][%cal Gg7f6,Gf6c3,Ga1g1]}) 21. Qg4 Qxg4 22. Rxg4 Rhg8 23. Rxg8 Rxg8 24. Kf1 Rg4 25. b3 $13 {[%cal Ga1e1] With an interesting endgame. The position is around equal, but White has slightly better chances.}) 15. O-O-O O-O-O 16. Be4 Qa5 17. Rhg1 e5 $1 (17... Qxa2 $5 18. Rxg7 Be8 19. Bb1 (19. Rg3 Qa5 20. h4 c5 21. Be5 Rxd1+ 22. Qxd1 f6 23. Ra3 Qb6 24. Qg4 $13) 19... Qa4 20. c5 Qh4 21. f4 $1 Rxd6 (21... Nc7 {[%cal Gc7d5] Looks like a human continuation, bringing the knight to the strong d5 square.} 22. Qe5 Nd5 23. Ba2 $1 Qf2 24. Bxd5 cxd5 25. Qc3 $14 {[%cal Gc3a5,Gd6e5]}) 22. cxd6 Qxf4+ 23. Rd2 $13 {Black has some compensation, but nothing more than that. The position is still dangerous and requires incredibly strong moves to survive.}) 18. Rxg7 $13 {[%cal Ge4b1] with mutual chances.}) (12... Qa5+ $6 {Besides 12...e5, few players try to bring the queen back to d8 with tempo and finish development.} 13. b4 $1 Nxb4 14. O-O $1 Na6 (14... c5 15. Rb1 Qd8 16. Bxc5 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Nbc6 18. Ne4 O-O 19. Nc3 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8][%cal Gh2h4,Ga2a4,Yf3c6,Yc5f8]}) 15. Qb3 Nf5 16. Nxf5 Qxf5 17. Kh1 $5 {[%cal Gf1g1] White has a few winning continuations, but I like the choice of strong Turkish GM Yilmaz} (17. Rad1 Nc5 18. Qe3 $18 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gd1d4,Gg1h1]}) 17... f6 (17... Bd7 $1 18. Qe3 $16) 18. Rg1 Kf7 {Unfortunately, Yilmaz didn’t continue his energetic attack well; in the end, he lost all his advantages. He could have finished the game with a beautiful sacrifice} 19. Bg4 $3 (19. Rae1 Nc5 $132 {Yilmaz,M (2641)-Raja,R (2524) Sharjah UAE 2024}) 19... Qa5 (19... Qe4+ 20. f3 $18) 20. Bxe6+ $1 Bxe6 (20... Kxe6 21. c5+ Kf5 22. Qd3+ Ke6 23. Qe4+ Kf7 24. Qe7+ {[%cal Ge7g7]}) 21. Qxb7+ Nc7 22. Bxc7 Qf5 23. Bb8+ $18 {[%cal Gb7a8]}) (12... O-O {This move directly enters dangerous lines where survival's hard without deep engine preparation.} 13. Ne4 Qa5+ 14. b4 Qd8 (14... Nxb4 $6 15. O-O Re8 16. Qd2 c5 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Rad1 f5 (18... Re8 19. Qg5 $18 {[%cal Gg1h1,Gf1g1]}) 19. Qd8+ Qxd8 20. Rxd8+ Kf7 21. Nd6+ Kf6 22. Rd1 $1 Nxa2 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Nxc8 Nc3 25. Rd3 Re8 26. Bxb7 (26. Rxc3 Rxc8 27. Bxb7 Rb8 28. Ba6 g5 $11) 26... Ne2+ 27. Kf1 Nf4 28. Rd7 $14 {[%cal Gb7a6,Gd7a7] Black definitely has some compensation for the piece, but it's going to be hard to prove it.}) 15. Rg1 Ng6 (15... f6 $6 {[%cal Ge6e5] Venkatesan,K (2202)-Smeets,K (2322) Prague CZE 2024} 16. Qe2 $1 {After this move, Black's position completely collapses.} Nf5 (16... Nc7 17. O-O-O Ne8 18. Bc5 Qc7 19. Nd6 $18) (16... e5 17. O-O-O $18) 17. O-O-O $1 Rf7 (17... Nxd6 18. Nxd6 $18) 18. Bh5 $1 Rd7 19. Qg4 Nc7 (19... Kh8 20. Bg6 $3 $18) 20. Bxc7 Qxc7 21. Nxf6+ Kh8 22. Nxd7 $18) 16. h4 $1 (16. Bxf8 Qxf8 17. a3 e5 18. Qd6 $13 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gb4b5] also looks good for White.}) 16... f5 17. Ng5 h6 18. Bh5 {I will leave this line here, since I highly doubt it's possible to find all of these engine moves for equality.} (18. Nh3 Nxh4 19. Bh5 f4 (19... e5 20. f4 $1 exf4 21. Qd4 Qf6 22. O-O-O Qxd4 23. Rxd4 $18 {[%csl Ya6,Rf8,Yh4]}) 20. Be5 Qxd1+ 21. Rxd1 g5 22. Nxf4 Nxb4 23. Ng6 Nxg6 24. Bxg6 c5 $1 {[%cal Gb4c6]} 25. f4 Nc6 26. Bd6 Rf6 27. Be4 $13 {[%csl Gd6,Ge4]}) 18... hxg5 19. Rxg5 (19. Bxg6 $5 g4 20. h5 e5 21. Qd2 Be6 22. O-O-O $13 {[%cal Gd2c3,Yf2f4,Yh5h6] The position looks very tempting for White.}) 19... Nxh4 20. f4 e5 $1 21. Bxe5 Qxd1+ 22. Rxd1 g6 23. Bxg6 Nf3+ $1 24. Ke2 Nxg5 25. fxg5 Rf7 $1 26. Rd8+ Rf8 27. Rd6 Rf7 28. Bxf7+ Kxf7 29. Rf6+ Kg8 30. Rh6 Kf8 $3 31. b5 cxb5 32. cxb5 b6 33. bxa6 Bxa6+ 34. Ke3 Ke7 $11) 13. Qb3 $1 {[%cal Ga1d1] Preparing 0-0-0 or simply Rd1 while simultaneously putting pressure on the b7 pawn.} (13. Qe2 $6 {was an interesting try by Wojtaszek in the 2024 Olympiad. Unfortunately, after} Bh3 $1 14. Ne4 Qh6 $17 {[%cal Re1c1,Ge8c8] Black's pieces suddenly become harmonious and dangerous. We can't castle, while a big threat is 15...0-0-0 followed by ...Rhe8!}) 13... O-O ({According to the engine,} 13... Ng6 {is the best move but hardly playable for a human. The king stays in the center, and there is no solution for castling in the near future.} 14. Be2 $13 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gh2h4] Overall, the position results in complex play, which favors the better-prepared player!} Nf4 $2 15. h4 $1 Qh6 16. Rd1 Nxe2 17. Nxe2 $1 $36 {[%cal Gh1g1,Yb7b6,Yb3f3]}) (13... Qf6 14. Ne4 $1 Qh6 15. Rd1 $1 $16 {/+-.}) 14. h4 $1 Qf6 15. Ne4 Qe6 16. O-O-O $16 Re8 17. Rhg1 Nf5 18. Bh5 $1 Nd4 (18... Qh6+ 19. Kb1 b6 20. Qf3 $1 Nc5 21. Bxc5 bxc5 22. Rg5 Be6 23. Rxf5 Bxf5 24. Qxf5 g6 25. Rg1 Re7 26. Qf3 Rd8 27. Bg4 Rd4 28. b3 $16 {[%csl Yc5,Yc6][%cal Gf3f6]}) 19. Qd3 g6 20. f4 $1 c5 21. fxe5 Nb4 22. Qf1 Qf5 23. Rxd4 $1 cxd4 24. Nf6+ Kh8 25. Bxb4 Rxe5 26. Bd1 Be6 27. Bd6 Bxc4 {Until this moment, Abdusattorov played perfectly. Here, he missed the chance to finish the game calmly. Abdusattorov,N (2716)-Erigaisi,A (2712) Doha 2023.} (27... d3 28. Qxf5 Rxf5 29. Bg4 Rf2 30. Be5 Rc2+ 31. Kd1 Bxg4+ 32. Nxg4+ Kg8 33. h5 $18) 28. Bxe5 $1 Qxf1 (28... Bxf1 29. Ng4+ Qxe5 30. Nxe5 Rc8+ 31. Kd2 $18 {[%cal Ge5f7]}) 29. Rxf1 Bxf1 30. Bf3 {[%csl Ge5,Gf6,Rh8]} Rc8+ 31. Kd2 {[%cal Gf3b7]} Rd8 (31... Rc5 32. Nd7+ Rxe5 33. Nxe5 $18) 32. Bxb7 Kg7 33. b4 $18 {[%csl Gb7,Ge5,Gf6] After 11.Bf3!?, White maintains the potential for rich and dynamic positions. The ideas we've explored introduce new ways to create serious practical problems for Black, increasing the chances of him stumbling. We've seen how easily Black can make mistakes, making preparation a key factor for success.} *

