{[%evp 0,23,26,26,24,-3,12,4,44,47,48,53,32,-8,28,38,21,0,27,-12,-32,-21,-22,-25,-14,-70]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ (5... c5 $5 {Probably the best sideline for Black, played by Kramnik in the 2018 FIDE Candidates. It definitely demands some precision from White.} 6. Nxc5 (6. dxc5 {is definitely an interesting alternative, but after} Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Nf6 8. Nd6+ Bxd6 9. cxd6 Ne4 {Gschnitzer,A (2431)-Gruca,M (2198) chess.com INT 2024} 10. Ke1 Nxd6 11. b3 Nc6 12. Ba3 Nf5 13. Bd3 $13 {[%csl Ga3,Gd3][%cal Ga1d1,Gg1e2,Gf7f6,Ge6e5] we have the bishop pair and a slightly more active position, but Black should be OK.}) (6. Nf3 {A logical move, but it doesn't benefit us. Black will trade many pieces with tempo.} cxd4 7. Qxd4 Bb4+ {Important intermezzo!} 8. Nc3 (8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Kxd2 Nc6 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bd3 Ke7 12. Kc3 f5 13. Ng3 g6 $11 {Gholami Orimi,M (2470)-Li,D (2563) Dubai UAE 2024}) 8... Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 10. Be3 Nf6 (10... Nc6 11. Ndb5 $16 {[%cal Gb5a7,Ga2a3] Hamidov,A (2307)-Shirov,A (2660) chess.com INT 2024}) 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Nc6 13. Rfd1 Bxc3 14. bxc3 b6 $11) 6... Nc6 {Here, I have analyzed a few possible options for White. In my opinion,} (6... Bxc5 $6 7. dxc5 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1e3]}) 7. Nb3 {gives us the best chance for some slight advantage.} (7. Ne2 $5 Nxd4 8. Ne4 Nxe2 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bxe2 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 $1 Nf6 (11... f5 12. a3 Be7 13. Ng5 Ke8 14. h4 Bf6 15. Rh3 Ne7 (15... e5 16. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c3]}) 16. f4 h6 17. Nf3 Nc6 18. Rb1 b6 19. Be3 Bb7 20. b4 $14 {We have a pleasant position, and I definitely like our long-term chances.}) 12. a3 Be7 13. Nc3 Bd7 14. Bf4 $13 {White gets a free-risk position, but Black is solid.}) (7. Nf3 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Bxc5 10. Nb5 Ke7 (10... Bb4+ $6 11. Ke2 $1 $14 {/ Batsiashvili,N (2462)-Radeva,V (2263) Custica SRB 2022}) 11. Nc7 Rb8 12. Bf4 Bb4+ 13. Ke2 $1 Bd6 14. Bxd6+ Kxd6 15. Nb5+ Ke7 16. Nxa7 Bd7 $11) 7... a5 $1 8. a4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Nxd4 10. Bxb4 Nxb3 11. Qxb3 Qb6 12. Nf3 axb4 13. Bd3 $1 (13. Qe3 $6 Qxe3+ 14. fxe3 {Cheng,B (2583)-Salimova,N (2390) Sitges ESP 2022} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Ga8a5]}) (13. Be2 Nf6 14. Ne5 Bd7 15. O-O O-O 16. Rfd1 Ne4 17. Nd3 Bc6 18. a5 Rxa5 19. Rxa5 Qxa5 20. Qxb4 Qxb4 21. Nxb4 $13 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) 13... Nf6 14. O-O O-O 15. Bc2 $13 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gf1e1] According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.20. We have a small, but long-lasting advantage.}) (5... Nf6 $6 6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Nf3 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Nd7 (9... O-O $2 10. O-O-O $36 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gf3g5] }) 10. Be2 (10. O-O-O {[%cal Gf1d3] is a good alternative.} c5 (10... O-O 11. Qe3 $16 {[%cal Re6e5,Rc6c5,Gf1d3]}) 11. Qe3 b6 12. d5 $14 {/}) 10... O-O 11. Qe3 $1 {[%cal Re6e5] Important move. Preventing ...e5 counterplay} b6 12. O-O Qe7 13. Rad1 Bb7 14. Rfe1 $14 {[%cal Ge2d3,Gd3c2,Yd7f6,Yc4c5] /. We will continue with Bd3 followed by Bc2, gaining control of the important b1-h7 diagonal. Against ..c5, we’ll be ready to respond with d5!, while ...Nf6 will be met with the well-known and typical c5!, closing the bishop on b7.}) (5... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Gg8f6]} 6. Nf3 Ngf6 7. Bd3 c5 $1 (7... Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Bb4+ (8... Nf6 9. Bc2 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Rc8,Gd4] Dominant structure by White. The light-squared bishop is closed, and it will be a long-term problem for Black.}) 9. Bd2 Qa5 10. O-O ({Another good alternative is} 10. a3 {, simply trading queens and enjoying a better middlegame.} Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c3,Gg2g4,Gh2h4]}) 10... Bxd2 11. Nxd2 O-O 12. Re1 $1 Nf6 13. Bf3 Rd8 14. Qc2 $1 Qc7 15. Qc3 $1 b6 {Ortega,L (2437)-Manganelli,G (2017) Porto San Giorgo 2003} 16. Rad1 $1 Bb7 (16... a5 17. h4 $1 $36 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 17. c5 $16 {[%csl Rb7]}) 8. O-O cxd4 9. Nxd4 Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Qf3 $14 {Our development is slightly more active, and we have a slightly better position.}) 6. Bd2 Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 Na6 (8... Nd7 $6 9. Nf3 c5 10. Bc3 Ngf6 (10... Ne7 $6 {was played a few times by the big triangle expert, Dragisa Blagojevic. Not the best move, but we need to know how to punish it.} 11. Qd2 $1 O-O 12. O-O-O Ng6 {Vaisser,A (2555)-Lagumina,G (2280) Mendrisio 1989. While everyone played the solid 13.g3 here, I don't see anything wrong with immediately} 13. h4 $1 $36 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gf3g5,Gh1e1]}) 11. Qd6 $1 {[%cal Re8g8]} a5 {[%cal Ga8a6]} (11... Qc6 {The most played move, but after simple} 12. Qxc6 (12. Qg3 $16) 12... bxc6 13. Nd2 $18 {[%csl Ra7,Rc5,Rc6][%cal Ge1c1] White has a winning position, as was the case in the game Polgar,Z (2550)-Georgiev,K (2615) Pardubice 1994}) 12. Rd1 Ra6 13. Qd2 O-O 14. O-O e5 (14... b6 $2 {Esposito,L (2212)-Lazic,M (2512) Verona 2005} 15. Bd3 $1 Qc6 16. Rfe1 Bb7 17. Qg5 $1 $40 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3,Gg5] +-}) 15. Bd3 Qg4 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 $16 {[%csl Gd3,Ge5] Bao,K (2221)-Duong,T (2373) Can Tho 2012}) (8... c5 $6 {Marshall Gambit, Tolush Variation, was a popular option in the '90s. With modern engines, we can claim an advantage after} 9. Bxc5 $1 Qxg2 10. Qd6 $1 Nd7 11. Bf3 Qg5 12. Ba3 Ne7 13. Be4 $3 $16 {[%cal Re7f5,Gg1f3]}) 9. Bd6 e5 {[%cal Gc8g4] Strongest sideline. Black wants to play ...Bg4, followed by queenside castle.} (9... b6 $6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge8c8]} 10. Nf3 Bb7 11. O-O $1 Rd8 (11... O-O-O {[%cal Rd8d1] At first, this pin seems unpleasant, but after} 12. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Re4,Rf7] it's obvious that the queen will remain trapped.} Qf5 13. g4 $1 {[%csl Rf5]} Qf4 (13... Qf6 14. f4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gg4g5]}) 14. Ng6 Qxd6 15. Qxd6 Rxd6 16. Nxh8 Rd7 {Trofimov,N (2306)-Shchemelev,P (2287) ICCF email 2017} 17. Rad1 Re7 18. Rd3 $18 {[%cal Gd3h3,Gf1d1,Gf2f4]}) 12. Ng5 $1 Qf5 13. f4 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ge2g4]} Ne7 (13... Nh6 {Zacurdajev,M (2400)-Vitiugov,N (2550) St Petersburg 2006} 14. Bh5 $1 {[%csl Gd6,Re8,Gh5] Preparing a beautiful Nxe6 threat.} Rd7 (14... Bc8 15. Bf3 $1 Bb7 16. g4 Qg6 17. h4 $18 {[%csl Gf4,Gg4,Rg6,Gh4]}) 15. Nxe6 $3 Qxe6 16. Re1 $18) 14. Bh5 $1 {[%csl Rf7]} O-O (14... g6 15. Bf3 Nc8 16. Ne4 Nxd6 17. Nxd6+ Rxd6 18. Qxd6 Qc5+ 19. Qxc5 Nxc5 20. b4 $18 {[%cal Gb4b5]}) 15. g4 Qf6 16. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Rh7]} Ng6 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Rad1 $18 {Kosyrev,V (2546)-Yudin,S (2442) Sochi 2006}) (9... Bd7 {Preparing to castle queenside.} 10. Nf3 $1 O-O-O 11. O-O ({A good alternative is} 11. c5 Be8 12. Rc1 $18 {[%cal Ge1g1] Black is completely paralyzed.}) 11... Be8 12. b4 Nh6 (12... c5 13. b5 Nc7 14. Bd3 Rxd6 15. Bxe4 Rxd1 16. Rfxd1 f5 17. Bc2 $18 {[%cal Gf3e5]}) 13. c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd6]} Nf5 ({It's possible to avoid Bxa6 with} 13... Nc7 {but after} 14. Re1 $18 {there's no good square for the queen. We threat strong ideas like Qa4 and Ne5.}) 14. Bxa6 bxa6 {Sagar,S (2285)-Balazs,G (2353) Kecskemet 2010} 15. Re1 Qg4 16. Qa4 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Ra7,Rc8][%cal Gf3e5]}) (9... Ne7 $2 {[%cal Ge7f5] There's no special idea behind this move; we simply finish our development while Black's king remains trapped in the center.} 10. Nf3 Nf5 (10... f6 {transpose to 9...f6}) 11. O-O $1 Nxd6 12. Qxd6 {[%csl Re8]} Qf5 (12... Qxe2 13. Rad1 $18 {[%cal Gd6d8]}) 13. Ne5 $1 $18 {[%cal Ge5c6,Yf5f6,Ye2h5]}) (9... Nh6 $6 10. Nf3 $1 f6 11. O-O {transpose to 9...f6}) (9... f6 $6 10. Nf3 $1 Nh6 $1 (10... Ne7 11. O-O $1 c5 12. Re1 Qc6 13. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%csl Gd6,Re8][%cal Gd1d2,Ge2h5]}) (10... Bd7 {Now it's too late for queenside castling. After} 11. O-O O-O-O 12. Bd3 Qg4 13. c5 $1 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gd1a4,Gd3a6] the position is completely lost for Black.} e5 (13... Nc7 14. h3 $1 Qh5 15. Qa4 $18 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ga5a7]}) 14. h3 Qe6 15. Qa4 Nc7 16. Bc4 Qf5 17. Qa5 Ne8 18. Bf7 {[%csl Ga5,Rc8,Gd6,Rd8,Re8,Gf7,Rg8,Rh8] 1-0 Bacrot,E (2715)-Filippov,V (2621) Moscow 2005. Beautiful game by Bacrot!}) 11. O-O Nf7 12. Re1 $1 c5 13. Bg3 Qc6 14. a3 e5 (14... Bd7 15. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd3e4]}) 15. Bxe5 $1 fxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bh5+ g6 18. Rxe5+ Kf7 19. Bf3 Qf6 20. Qd5+ Kg7 21. Rae1 Rf8 22. Re7+ Kh8 23. h4 $18 {Ragnarsson,J (2137)-Velde,M (2159) ICCF email 2019}) (9... c5 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6]} 10. Nf3 Bd7 {11.0-0 is also a good option for Black, but I like this aggressive move. We prevent ...Bc6, followed by queenside castle.} 11. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge1g1,Ge5d7]} Ne7 12. Nxd7 Rd8 13. Ne5 Nc6 14. f3 Rxd6 15. Qxd6 Qxe5 16. Qxe5 Nxe5 17. f4 $18 {[%cal Ge2f3] It shouldn't be hard to capitalize on this advantage.}) 10. Nf3 Bg4 (10... f6 $5 11. O-O Be6 {Dyballa,M (2265)-Matlak,M (2420) Naleczow 1989} (11... Bf5 12. Nxe5 $1 {Beautiful improvement over the previous game. Of course, 12.c5 is also a good move, but let's finish the game in style!} (12. c5 $18 {Izoria,Z (2556)-Yagupov,I (2474) Batumi 2002}) 12... fxe5 13. Bh5+ $1 Bg6 14. Re1 Bxh5 15. Qxh5+ Qg6 16. Qxe5+ Kf7 17. Re3 $18 {[%cal Ge3f3,Gf3g3,Rg8h6,Re5e7,Re7b7]}) 12. Re1 $1 O-O-O 13. Bd3 $1 Qg4 14. h3 Qh5 15. c5 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Rc8][%cal Gd3a6,Gd1a4] With the ideas we saw in the previous lines, it's +3, and we should capitalize on this advantage soon.}) 11. O-O O-O-O {[%cal Rd8d1] The main position of this sideline. Here, I recommend continuing with} 12. Bd3 $1 (12. b4 {White's most common continuation, but after} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e8] followed by Ne8, it seems that Black is OK.} 13. c5 Ne8 $11) 12... Qf4 13. Bxe5 Qxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxd1 15. Bf5+ $1 (15. Nxf7 Bg4 $1 16. h3 Be6 17. Nxd8 Kxd8 18. Rad1 Bd7 19. f4 Ne7 20. g4 g6 $11) 15... Kc7 16. Nxf7 $1 Be2 {is probably the best continuation for Black. Recently played in the Championship of Bangladesh, the game continued:} (16... Bh5 $6 17. Nxd8 Kxd8 {Aronian,L (2752)-Vallejo Pons,F (2650) Morelia/Linares 2006} 18. f3 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rh8][%cal Ga1d1,Gf1e1] Black is lacking in development, while our rooks will join the game quickly.} (18. g4 {Gschnitzer,A (2404)-Perestjuk,M (2116) Biel SUI 2020} Nh6 $1 $11)) (16... Nh6 $5 17. Nxd8 Rxd8 18. Bxh7 Be2 19. Rfc1 Rd2 20. b3 Nb4 {Tait,J (2418)-Kugler,K (2509) ICCF WS 2006} 21. f3 $1 a5 22. a3 Nd3 23. Bxd3 Bxd3 (23... Rxd3 $4 24. Kf2 $1 Rd2 25. Ke3 Rb2 26. g4 $18 {[%csl Re2,Rh6]}) 24. Rd1 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Bc2 26. Re1 Bxb3 27. Re7+ $13 {[%csl Gf3,Gg2,Yg7,Gh2][%cal Gc4c5,Gg2g4] According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.20. Black's position seems OK, but it's slightly unpleasant due to our chances on the queenside.}) 17. Rfe1 Nh6 18. Rxe2 Nxf5 (18... Nxf7 19. Re7+ Kb8 20. Rxf7 g6 21. Be4 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Ge4,Yg6,Yh7][%cal Gf2f3,Gh2h4]}) 19. Nxh8 Rxh8 20. g4 (20. Rd1 Rd8 21. Rxd8 Kxd8 22. f4 $13 {[%cal Gg2g4]}) 20... Nd6 $2 {At first, it seems like a much more logical move than 20...Nh4, but after} (20... Nh4 {was a better continuation.} 21. Re7+ Kb6 22. a3 $13 {[%cal Ga1d1,Ge7g7,Gb2b4] According to the engine, Black has enough counterplay for equality, but he needs to play a lot of precise moves.}) 21. Re7+ Kb6 22. Rd1 Nxc4 23. b3 Na3 24. Rxg7 h6 25. Rdd7 $18 {[%cal Gg7h7,Gh2h4] We have a completely winning position.} (25. f4 $16 {Mohammad Fahad,R (2437)-Rahman,Z (2423) Dhaka BAN 2024}) *

