{[%evp 0,6,25,26,19,-8,0,8,28]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 (5... Nf6 6. e3 Bd6 7. Bxd6 ({Recently played by a former Women's World Chess Championship challenger, this move order with Qf3 is not as dangerous as in the main line since it allows some ...Bg4 ideas. However, it could be used as a potential alternative to our usual Bd3-Nge2 setup.} 7. Qf3 O-O 8. Bd3 $13 {Lei,T (2549)-Li Ruofan (2318) Shaoxing CHN 2024}) 7... Qxd6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 (9... b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 10. Nf4 $5 {[%cal Gd1f3]} Na6 (10... Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Qa4 Nb8 13. O-O c6 14. Rac1 a5 15. Rfd1 Na6 (15... Nbd7 16. Rd2 Rfc8 17. Rdc2 $14 {[%cal Gc3e2]}) 16. Qc2 {[%csl Rc6,Gf5][%cal Gc2f5] I think we have a few more ways to press for an advantage, but I like placing the queen on f5 - well-known idea from Queen's Gambit structures.} Rfc8 17. Qf5 $14 {[%cal Gf4d3,Gc3a4,Gd1d2,Gd2c2] We’ll proceed with Rd2-Rdc2 and Nd3-e5, putting pressure on c6. The queen on f5 is ideally placed, provoking potential weaknesses around the king while controlling the h3-c8 diagonal. Our position is slightly better.}) (10... Bb7 11. Qf3 $5 c5 12. O-O Rd8 (12... cxd4 13. Nb5 Qe5 14. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rd5] It's a risk-free position. We're playing against an isolated pawn, and Black has no attack.}) (12... Nc6 $2 {is just a blunder..} 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Nfxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 $16) 13. Rfd1 $5 Nc6 14. dxc5 bxc5 (14... Qxc5 15. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Rd5]}) 15. Ncxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Qxd5 17. Nxd5 Rxd5 18. Bh7+ Kxh7 19. Rxd5 c4 20. Rad1 $1 (20. Rc5 Rd8 $1 {Active play is the only chance to save the game.} 21. Rxc4 Rd2 22. b4 a6 23. h3 Ne5 $1 24. Rd4 Rxd4 25. exd4 Nd3 26. Rb1 Bc6 {In this version, it seems that Black can hold the endgame.}) 20... f6 21. Rc5 Ne5 22. Rd6 $14 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gf2f4] According to the engine, the position is nearly equal, but Black needs to play perfectly to hold it. We're a pawn up, and if we capture the c4 pawn, our winning chances increase significantly.}) 11. O-O c6 12. Rc1 Nc7 13. Qf3 Ne6 14. Nh5 Nxh5 15. Qxh5 a5 16. Rfd1 $13 {[%cal Gc3e2,Gc1c3] Following the same ideas as before, doubling rooks on the c-file to pressure the c6 pawn and preparing Ne2-h4.We have a comfortable position.}) (9... a6 $6 {[%cal Gb8c6] Here, Petrov continues with the original idea Nf4-Qf3, but I suggest another approach.} 10. O-O (10. Nf4 Nc6 11. Qf3 Ne7 12. h3 Bd7 13. O-O $13 {Petrov,N (2563)-Draskovic,L (2485) Podgorica MNE 2024}) 10... Nc6 11. Rc1 Ne7 12. Ng3 $1 {[%csl Gf5] Controlling the f5 square.} Re8 13. Re1 Bd7 14. a3 Rac8 15. Bb1 $14 {[%cal Gd1c2,Yf2f3,Ye3e4] We'll form a battery and gradually prepare f3-e4.}) 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge3e4] The whole point of this setup is to prepare f3-e4.} Nf8 12. Rac1 Qe7 {[%cal Rf2f3]} (12... c6 $6 13. f3 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd3b1,Ge2g3,Ge3e4] /}) 13. Rfe1 c6 14. Nf4 Ne6 15. Bb1 $1 {[%cal Gf2f3]} ({Here} 15. f3 $6 {would be too early.} Nxf4 16. exf4 Qb4 $132) 15... Nxf4 (15... Bd7 {doesn't change our plan} 16. f3 $1 $14) 16. exf4 Qd6 17. Re5 {[%csl Ge5]} Be6 18. h3 $14 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gc1e1]}) 6. e3 Bd6 (6... Bf5 7. f3 $5 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4] We are preparing a pawn storm and gaining a space advantage on the kingside. Our king will be safe on the f2 square.} (7. g4 $5 {is another way of aggressive play!} Bh7 8. h4 Bd6 9. Nh3 Ne7 {Ambartsumova,K (2418)-Osmak,Y (2452) FIDE Online Arena INT 2024} 10. Rg1 $1 $36 {[%cal Gd1f3,Ye1c1]}) 7... Bd6 {allows us to take control of the center after} (7... Nf6 8. g4 Bh7 9. h4 Bd6 10. Nge2 Qe7 11. Kf2 Na6 12. g5 $1 (12. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11 {Ju,W (2564)-Paehtz,E (2471) Baku AZE 2023}) 12... Nd7 (12... Nh5 $2 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Bh3 $18 {[%cal Re8c8,Re8g8]}) 13. Rc1 $1 {Important move. We delay 0-0-0 and prepare Bh3} Nc7 (13... O-O-O 14. Nxd5 $18) 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Bh3 O-O-O 16. Qg1 $1 $14 {[%cal Gg1g3] A beautiful move. After the exchange of queens, I believe we have better chances on the kingside. Black can't avoid it, as failing to do so would allow Nxd5!, which would be devastating for Black.}) 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. e4 $1 Bh7 10. e5 Qb4 11. Qd2 Nd7 12. f4 $14 {According to the engine, the position is close to equal, and to keep that balance, Black needs to play a lot of precise moves.}) 7. Qf3 $5 {is an excellent preparatory move for initiating an aggressive kingside attack with h3 and g4. By positioning the queen on f3, White supports the pawn advance and generates tactical and positional threats against Black’s setup. This approach forces Black to respond carefully, as even minor inaccuracies can result in significant weaknesses on the kingside.} Nf6 (7... Ne7 $5 8. h4 $5 {In the spirit of this course, we are seeking maximum aggression!} (8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Bd3 Nd7 10. Nge2 Nf6 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O {is a calmer way to play this position.}) 8... O-O (8... Bxf4 9. Qxf4 Bf5 10. g4 Bh7 11. Rd1 (11. g5 Bf5 (11... Bc2 {I highly doubt that anyone will play such an engine move, but even so, after} 12. Bh3 {[%cal Gg1e2,Ge2g3] we definitely maintain some initiative on the kingside.}) 12. Nge2 $13 {[%cal Ge2g3]}) 11... Nd7 12. Nge2 a5 13. Ng3 {White has a pleasant position, while Black must decide what to do with his king. If Black castles kingside at any point, we will be ready to push g5!}) 9. Bd3 (9. h5 $5 Be6 $1 (9... c5 $6 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bd3 Nbc6 12. Nge2 Bd6 13. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Rd5] /}) 10. O-O-O (10. g4 c5 $1 11. Bd3 Nbc6 12. Nge2 Bxf4 13. Qxf4 Qb8 $11) 10... c5 11. Bd3 Nbc6 12. Nge2 Bxf4 13. Qxf4 c4 14. Bb1 f5 $132 {[%cal Rg2g4,Gd8a5]}) (9. g4 c5 $1 {Only move for equality!} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O-O (11. g5 h5 $1) 11... Nbc6 12. Nge2 Be6 13. g5 h5 $3 14. Qxh5 Rc8 15. Bh3 Bxh3 16. Rxh3 Qb6 $1 17. Qg4 Na5 {According to the engine, Black has enough counterplay, but he needs to find a lot of precise moves!}) 9... Bf5 $1 10. Bxf5 Nxf5 11. Nge2 Bxf4 12. Qxf4 Nd6 13. g4 Na6 14. O-O-O $13 {[%cal Ge2g3,Gg3f5,Yg4g5] We will aim to open the g-file and create an attack.}) 8. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4]} O-O 9. Bd3 Re8 10. Nge2 Bxf4 11. Nxf4 a5 12. g4 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] We’ve achieved the position we aim for and are now ready to play 0-0-0 and follow up with Rdg1 to launch a powerful attack!} *

