{[%evp 0,12,23,8,7,11,11,-11,5,11,24,13,20,0,37]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Bf4 Nf6 (4... Bd6 5. Nh3 {will transpose to the main line.}) 5. e3 (5. c5 $5 {Rare, but very interesting idea. I think Black should react here with b6-a5.} b6 $1 (5... Be7 6. e3 c6 $6 (6... O-O 7. h4 $5 b6 8. g4 Nxg4 9. Qxg4 e5 {Gu,X (2157)-Palczert,M (2299) Budapest HUN 2024} 10. Qg2 $1 exf4 11. Nxd5 c6 12. Nxf4 bxc5 13. O-O-O $14 {[%cal Gf4h5,Gg1e2,Gh1g1]}) 7. Bd3 (7. b4 $1) 7... Nbd7 8. b4 a5 9. a3 axb4 10. axb4 Rxa1 11. Qxa1 Nh5 12. Nf3 Nxf4 13. exf4 $16 {Petkov,M (2526)-Makridis,D (2387) Vrnjacka Banja SRB 2023}) (5... Nh5 {Lysyj,I (2597)-Kazhgaleyev,M (2499) Chelyabinsk RUS 2023} 6. Be5 $1 Nc6 7. Nf3 f6 8. Bg3 Nxg3 9. hxg3 g5 10. e3 Bg7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 6. b4 a5 $1 7. a3 Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. e3 Ne4 $1 $132) 5... Bd6 {By far the most common move.} (5... Bb4 {is a solid and principled move. By placing the bishop on b4, Black pins the knight on c3, which can be quite uncomfortable for White, as it limits the mobility of the knight and increases the pressure on the center.} 6. Rc1 O-O 7. Nf3 {Critical moment for Black. He needs to continue with} c5 $1 (7... Nbd7 8. c5 $1 $14) (7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. O-O cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 11. Bd3 Bd6 12. Be5 $14 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gh2h4] White has a good version of the IQP.}) (7... b6 8. g4 $3 Ne4 (8... dxc4 9. g5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 $16 {[%cal Gh1g1]}) 9. h4 $1 $40 {[%cal Gg4g5] }) 8. dxc5 Nbd7 9. Bd6 Re8 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bb5 Qa5 12. Qa4 Qxa4 13. Bxa4 Rd8 14. O-O Bxc5 15. Bg3 Nxc3 16. Rxc3 Be7 17. Bc7 Rf8 18. Rd1 $13 {At the end of this long, almost forced line, the engine evaluates the position as roughly equal, but I wouldn't mind playing it. It already looks quite risky after 11.Bb5.}) (5... c5 6. Nf3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 a6 {Giri,A (2768)-Yu Yangyi (2729) chess.com INT 2023} 8. Rc1 $1 {I chose this move because it demands precise moves from Black to maintain equality.} Nbd7 $1 (8... Be7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5]}) (8... Nc6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Ya6,Yc6,Yd5][%cal Ge1g1,Gd1a4]}) 9. Qa4 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Bc5 11. Bxe6 O-O $1 (11... Bxd4 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd4 $16) (11... fxe6 12. Nxe6 $18 {[%cal Ge6c7]}) 12. Bxd7 Bxd7 13. Qd1 $13 {Black definitely has compensation here, but proving it won't be easy.}) 6. Nh3 $5 {[%cal Gg2g4] Original idea by famous German GM Bluebaum Matthias. 6.Nh3!? is a rare and somewhat unconventional choice, but it serves a specific strategic purpose. By placing the knight on h3, White prepares for a flexible kingside attack and keeps options open for future play.} O-O {A brave move, which can be dangerous for Black if he is not well-prepared.} ({One of the solid moves Black can play is} 6... Nc6 7. c5 (7. g4 e5 $17) 7... Bxf4 8. Nxf4 O-O 9. Bb5 Ne7 10. O-O c6 11. Bd3 $13 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc3e2]}) (6... Be7 $5 7. cxd5 (7. Bg3 {[%cal Gh3f4]} O-O 8. Nf4 c5 $1 (8... dxc4 $6 9. Bxc4 a6 10. a4 $16 Nbd7 $2 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Nxe6 $18 Qe8 13. Nxc7 Qg6 14. Nxa8 $18 {Bluebaum,M (2654)-Fiorito,F (2434) chess.com INT 2024}) 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Ncxd5 exd5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nxd5 Be6 13. Nc3 Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 Bb4 {[%cal Ge6a2,Gf8c8]} 15. a3 Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 Rc8 $44 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc8c3,Gc3a3]}) 7... exd5 8. Bg3 O-O 9. Nf4 Re8 10. Be2 c6 {[%cal Gc8f5] Here, we have an interesting Queen's Gambit with the knight on f4 instead of f3. I would take this chance and try to prepare f3-e4 in the future.} 11. Qc2 Nbd7 12. O-O a5 13. f3 Nf8 14. Bd3 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gc2d2] With mutual chances.}) (6... b6 $5 {Definitely not the right idea in this setup. We can switch to a strategic approach thanks to the better pawn structure.} 7. Rc1 $1 Bb7 (7... a6 $6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Be5 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gh3f4]}) (7... c6 8. a3 $14 {[%cal Gg2g4]}) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 (8... exd5 9. Bxd6 {[%cal Gc3b5]} cxd6 10. Nf4 $18 {[%csl Rd5,Rd6]}) 9. Bb5+ $1 {Very important move - we're provoking c6 with tempo!} c6 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Ba4 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Rb8d7]} (11. Bd3 $14 {is also a reasonable move. Typically, the bishop goes there after provoking c6, but in this position, we prefer the bishop on a4 to make it harder for Black to develop, as c6 is a significant weakness} Bb4+ 12. Kf1 Nd7 13. Ng1 $1 {[%cal Gg1e2] Time to improve the knight!} Qf6 14. Ne2 Bd6 (14... O-O 15. Ng3 $18 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gd1g4]}) 15. h4 $1 $14 {/}) 11... O-O (11... Bb4+ 12. Kf1 {[%cal Rb8d7]} O-O 13. Qg4 $16 {[%cal Gf4e5,Gg4g3]} (13. g4 $5 $14 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gg4g5]})) 12. Qg4 Qf6 13. O-O $14 {[%csl Ga4,Rb8,Rc6][%cal Gg4g3,Gh3f4,Gh2h4] /. We'll continue improving our position, while Black's development is held back by the c6 weakness. The key question is how he'll deal with it!? 13...b5 would leave c5 as a strong outpost for us, while 13...c5 would give him a poor version of hanging pawns, which would be easy targets.}) ({I believe that} 6... c5 $6 {is too early here. After} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. cxd5 exd5 (8... Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 (9... Qxd5 $6 10. Nf4 Qd8 (10... Qd6 11. Rc1 $16 {[%cal Rc1c8]}) 11. dxc5 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Ke7 13. Bb5 $1 $16 {[%cal Gf4d3]}) 10. Nf4 $14) 9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. Nf4 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf1b5,Ga1c1] /. Easy play against the isolated pawn. Beautiful strategic position.}) (6... Bxf4 7. Nxf4 dxc4 (7... O-O 8. cxd5 (8. h4 $5 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nc6 10. Bb3 e5 11. Ng6 Re8 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ 13. Rxd1 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Rxe5 15. Rd8+ Re8 16. Rxe8+ Nxe8 17. f3 Kf8 18. Kf2 $13 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh4h5,Ge3e4]}) 8... Nxd5 (8... exd5 $6 9. f3 Qd6 (9... Re8 10. Qd2 g5 11. Nfe2 Qe7 12. Kf2 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Ge2g3]}) 10. Qd2 Rd8 11. g4 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh2h4] /+-}) 9. Nfxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 c6 (10... Nc6 11. O-O Ne7 12. Qh5 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gf1c1]}) 11. O-O Nd7 12. b4 $14 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Ga2a4,Gb4b5] We have a pleasant version of the Queen's Gambit.}) 8. Bxc4 c5 9. dxc5 Qxd1+ (9... Qe7 10. Qd6 $16) 10. Rxd1 $16) (6... g5 $6 {Wild and free..} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 {[%csl Rh3]} 8. f4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd1f3]} (8. Ng1 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4]})) 7. g4 $1 {is a bold and aggressive choice. By advancing the g-pawn, White intends to initiate a kingside attack, directly challenging Black's kingside structure. This move is particularly striking as it exposes White's kingside but also creates immediate threats against Black's position, forcing Black to react carefully.} Bxf4 (7... Nc6 $6 8. g5 Ne4 (8... hxg5 9. Bxg5 $18 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gd1f3]}) 9. gxh6 g6 10. Rg1 $16) (7... c5 $5 {aims to slow down White's potential kingside attack, especially following White’s aggressive g4 push. By gaining space on the queenside, Black hopes to balance the game and create counter-threats before White can fully build up a kingside initiative.} 8. g5 hxg5 9. Bxg5 cxd4 (9... Nc6 10. dxc5 $1) 10. Qxd4 Nc6 11. Bxf6 Nxd4 12. Bxd8 Nc2+ 13. Kd2 Nxa1 14. Bh4 {[%csl Ra1] The positions arising are complicated but not better for Black. Nevertheless, he needs to play a lot of computer moves to achieve equality!}) (7... Bb4 $2 {[%cal Gf6e4] Bluebaum,M (2649)-Boyer,M (2432) chess.com INT 2024} 8. g5 $1 Ne4 9. gxh6 $1 {We are not afraid of the pin. The king will be safe on e2, while Rg1 will be a deadly threat!} g6 (9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bxc3+ 11. Ke2 g6 12. Bg5 f6 13. Qd3 Kh7 14. Qxc3 fxg5 15. Rg1 g4 16. Rxg4 e5 17. Rg3 {[%cal Gh3g5]} Bxh3 18. Bxh3 Qf6 19. cxd5 $1 Qxf2+ 20. Kd1 {[%cal Gc3c7]} Na6 21. dxe5 Rad8 22. e4 Nc5 23. e6 $18 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6] Incredible position! Our king is in the center, but Black can't exploit that. The next move is 24.Rg2, and Black can resign.}) 10. Qc2 e5 $5 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 11. Bxe5 Bf5 12. Rg1 $1 {Once again, we are not afraid of ghosts! 12...Nxc3 is not possible due to 13.Qf5! +-} Nd7 13. Nf4 c6 14. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Ye5g7,Yf8e8]}) 8. Nxf4 dxc4 $1 (8... c5 9. dxc5 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nbd7 11. Nd3 $1 Nxc5 12. Nxc5 Qc7 13. Nxe6 (13. Qd4 Rd8 14. Nb5 Rxd4 15. Nxc7 Rxc4 16. Nxa8 Rxc5 17. O-O Bd7 $11) 13... Qc6 14. O-O Bxe6 15. Bxe6 Qxe6 16. h3 $13 {According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.20, and we are a pawn up. Black still needs to prove compensation. Many players would play 16...Rfd8 instantly, but after 16. Qf3!, White has a dominant position. The only way to fight for equality is 16...Rac8-Rc5, but it's hard to imagine anyone playing that without deep preparation.}) 9. h4 $5 {[%cal Gg4g5]} (9. Bxc4 {is probably the most solid move in this position.} Nc6 10. h3 (10. h4 e5 $1 $17) 10... Re8 11. O-O e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Bb3 $13 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc3d5] The position is equal, but there's still a lot of play left; a long game is ahead of us.}) 9... c5 $1 10. dxc5 (10. g5 cxd4 11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. exd4 Ng4 13. Bxc4 Rd8 14. d5 Ne5 15. Be2 exd5 16. Nfxd5 Nbc6 $11) 10... Qxd1+ (10... e5 {is also possible, but after} 11. Nfd5 Be6 12. Bxc4 Nxg4 13. Qf3 (13. f3 Nf6 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Ne4 Qe7 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qd6 Qf7 18. O-O-O Nc6 $11) 13... Nd7 14. Rd1 Nxc5 15. Qg3 $36 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gc4e2] the position seems a little bit more unpleasant for Black.}) 11. Rxd1 Nxg4 12. Bxc4 Ne5 13. Be2 Na6 14. Rg1 Nxc5 15. b4 Ncd7 16. Ne4 $13 {[%cal Gf4h5,Gf2f4,Ge4d6] According to the engine, the position is equal, but it still contains venom. Black must be careful. The general conclusion is that this line can be dangerous for Black if not prepared well. After 6.Nh3!?, the position we have is new and unexplored in OTB games, and can be an interesting surprise weapon!} *

