{[%evp 0,22,24,24,24,-4,6,-4,46,26,25,29,23,34,53,39,61,61,49,50,50,26,37,35,35]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 (4... cxd4 {is analyzed in the next chapter.}) 5. Nf3 Nc6 (5... Nf6 6. Bg5 Be6 {is also analyzed in the next chapter.}) 6. dxc5 d4 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. Rc1 Qb6 (10... Qd6 $2 11. Bc3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rd4,Rd6]}) 11. e3 Nf6 12. Bc4 dxe3 (12... O-O 13. O-O Be6 $1 {Although played in only a few games, this move seems to offer the best chance of fighting for equality.} (13... Bg4 14. exd4 Nxd4 15. Be3 Bxf3 16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. Bxd4 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] We have the bishop pair and a slightly better position. From what I can see, in the database, White scores 83.3%.}) 14. Bxe6 (14. b3 Bxc4 (14... dxe3 $6 15. Bxe3 Qa5 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qe2 Rfe8 18. Rc5 $16 {Lampert,J (2511)-Meinhardt,M (2374) Karlsruhe GER 2017}) 15. Rxc4 dxe3 16. Bxe3 Qa5 $11) 14... fxe6 15. Qc2 Rac8 16. Qb1 h6 $5 {Gonda,L (2547)-Lizak,P (2450) Budapest 2015. At this moment, Gonda missed} (16... Rcd8 $13 {with mutual chances.}) 17. exd4 $1 Nxd4 18. Rxc8 Nxf3+ (18... Rxc8 19. Bxh6 $1) 19. gxf3 Rxc8 20. Bxh6 $1 $14 {which would have left us a full pawn up.}) 13. Bxe3 Qb4+ 14. Kf1 $5 {An interesting move, played in only three games, which definitely demands precision from Black. Notice that 14...0-0 is not possible due to 15.Bc5! +-} (14. Bd2 Qe7+ 15. Be2 O-O 16. O-O $13 {[%csl Gd2,Ge2] With another risk-free position, Black remains solid, but we definitely need to demonstrate our bishop-pair technique!}) 14... Be6 $8 (14... Ne4 $2 15. Qd5 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gd5f7]} Qe7 {Colovic,A (2456)-Ivell,N (2244) Birmingham ENG 2015} 16. Re1 $1 Nf6 17. Qc5 $18 Nd7 18. Qxe7+ Nxe7 19. Bd4 $18 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Re7,Re8][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5]}) (14... O-O 15. Bc5 $18) (14... Bg4 15. Bc5 $18 {[%cal Gd1e2]}) 15. Qe2 {[%cal Gf3g5]} (15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Qe2 {[%cal Re8g8,Re3c5]} Qa5 $5 {Krasenkow,M (2604)-Koch,J (2484) Belfort 2012} ({Just like in the main line,} 16... Rd8 $1 {was a necessary move, but not an easy one!} 17. h4 $13 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh1h4]}) 17. Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re8g8]} Qxa2 18. g3 h6 19. Kg2 Kf7 20. Rhd1 {[%cal Ge2b5]} Rhd8 (20... a6 21. Rc3 $1 Qa4 22. Rd6 {[%cal Gf3d4] The position already looks very unpleasant for Black; he is under significant pressure, and it’s hard to see how he can hold things together.}) 21. Qb5 $13 {White has a slightly more pleasant position, and with one imprecise move, Black's position could crumble.}) 15... Rd8 $1 (15... h6 {[%cal Rf3g5]} 16. Bd4 $1 $14) (15... O-O $2 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Bc5 $18) 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5,Re8g8,Re3c5] My novelty. From the beginning, the entire idea was to prevent Black from castling short and to exploit the weaknesses on e6. Now, my plan is to push h5 and bring the rook into the game via the h4 square, increasing pressure on Black's kingside and further weakening his position.} (17. Bc5 Qe4 18. Qxe4 Nxe4 19. Be3 Nf6 20. Ke2 O-O 21. Rhd1 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 h6 23. Rd6 Kf7 24. Nd4 Nxd4+ 25. Bxd4 b6 {Koneru,H (2545)-Lei,T (2548) Stavanger NOR 2024. Here, Koneru missed the chance to enjoy a slightly better endgame, where she could have slowly applied pressure on Black.} 26. Rc6 $1 Nd5 27. Be5 $13 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg2g4]}) 17... Qe4 (17... O-O 18. Bc5 $18 {[%csl Rb4,Rf8]}) (17... Qa5 18. Bc5 {[%cal Re8g8]} Qxa2 19. Ng5 e5 20. Rh3 $1 Qd5 21. Qc2 $1 Rd7 $1 (21... Qd2 22. Qb1 Qd5 23. Kg1 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5]}) 22. Rf3 $36 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5] We continue to apply pressure, but Black should be able to hold and maintain balance despite the ongoing threats. The position remains tense, yet with accurate defense, Black can manage to guard the key weaknesses.}) 18. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6]} h6 (18... O-O $6 19. Rh4 $1 Qf5 20. h6 $1 $14) 19. Rh4 Qf5 20. Bc5 $13 {[%cal Re8g8,Gh4c4,Gf1g1] According to the engine, Black's position is okay, but I like our long-term chances. It's hard for Black to castle, and the e6 pawn is a long-term weakness.} *

