{[%evp 0,22,24,24,24,-4,6,-4,46,26,25,29,23,34,53,39,61,61,49,50,50,26,37,35,35]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 (4... cxd4 5. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 8. Qd1 (8. Qb3 $5 {brings dynamic tension to the position and forces Black to respond with precision} Na6 $1 9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2 Rc8 11. e3 Nce4 $1 (11... Na4 $1 12. Bd3 Bb4 13. Bd2 Nd5 14. O-O Ndxc3 15. bxc3 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Rxc3 17. Qd2 {Here, the position could be a bit risky. Black should continue with Rc5} Rc5 $1 {followed by Qc7, forming a battery on the important c-file.} (17... Qe7 $2 {is a good example of how Black can easily lose his way in this position.} 18. Bc2 Qf6 {Materia,M (2457)-Durak,C (2442) Prague CZE 2024} 19. Rac1 $1 Nb6 20. Bf5 $3 $18) 18. Rac1 Qc7 19. h4 O-O 20. Ng5 h6 21. Ne4 Qa5 22. Qxa5 Rxa5 23. Rc7 Bf5 $11) 12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd5 (13... Bb4 14. O-O Bxc3 15. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gc1a3]}) 14. Qb3 $1 Nxc3 15. O-O Ba4 16. Qxb7 Bc6 17. Qa6 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Bd6 19. Bf5 Rc7 20. f4 $13 {Santos Latasa,J (2655)-Dragnev,V (2561) Vrnjacka Banja SRB 2023. It's an unclear position, but Black definitely has compensation.}) (8. Qxb7 $6 {doesn't make sense, as it allows Black to develop quickly.} Nc6 9. Qb3 Rb8 10. Qd1 Bb4 $1 {Toncheva,N (2194)-Mikhalevski,V (2517) Braila ROU 2022} (10... Bc5 $6 11. Nf3 O-O 12. e3 $14 Qe7 13. Be2 Rfd8 14. O-O Bf5 15. Qa4 $16 {Paikens,R (2165)-Kaganskiy,G (2180) chess.com INT 2024}) 11. Nf3 O-O 12. e3 Ne4 13. Bd2 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qf6 16. Qc1 Bh3 (16... Qg6 17. Be2 Qxg2 18. Rg1 Qh3 19. c4 Qf5 $132) 17. Nd2 Bg4 $132 {[%cal Gc6e5]}) 8... Bc5 9. Nf3 O-O (9... Nc6 10. a3 $1 Qe7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Here, Black's clear intention is to castle long and launch a quick attack with g5-g4.} 11. Bg5 $1 {By removing the potentially dangerous knight, we also trade off the bishop, allowing us to play e3 without locking it in on c1.} O-O-O (11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. e3 (13. Rc1 Bb6 14. e3 Rd8 15. Qc2 (15. Bc4 $1 $16) 15... Bf5 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Be2 $14 {/}) 13... O-O-O (13... Rd8 14. Be2 $1 O-O 15. O-O Bb6 16. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1] Black has the bishop pair, but no real attacking prospects. I don't see sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 14. Be2 g5 15. O-O {We simply ignore it.} Bf5 (15... g4 {just helps us speed up our attack.} 16. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4]} Qg6 17. Rc1 $18 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd2c4]}) 16. Qa4 g4 {[%cal Rf3d2]} 17. Ne1 $1 h5 18. Ne4 Qe7 19. Nxc5 Qxc5 20. b4 $16 {[%cal Ge1d3,Ga1c1,Gc5c3]}) 12. e3 $1 Bf5 13. Qa4 $1 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Kobo,O (2484)-Kotrotsos,V (2259) Paleochora GRE 2019} 15. Qb5 $1 Bb6 16. Rc1 $18 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Gb2b4]}) 10. e3 {Our goal is to stay solid for the next few moves, gradually improve our piece placement, and patiently build our position.} Qe7 11. Be2 Nc6 12. O-O Rfd8 (12... Ne5 13. Qb3 $1 b5 14. Rd1 Rad8 15. a3 Rfe8 16. h3 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2e1,Ga1c1,Gf3d4] We've achieved a solid position to work with. We plan to continue slowly with Bd2-Be1, followed by Nd4. Black's position is active, but nothing extraordinary. He still has a long road ahead to prove any compensation.}) 13. Qc2 $1 (13. Qb3 $5 a6 $1 14. Bd2 Be6 15. Qc2 Nb4 16. Qb1 Bg4 17. Rd1 g6 $1 {[%cal Gg4f5] It now becomes clear that Puranik had prepared deeply. He memorized numerous engine moves just to reach a slightly worse endgame.} 18. e4 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Nd3 20. Be3 Bxe3 21. Rxd3 Ba7 $11 {Ivic,V (2599)-Puranik,A (2639) Bajina Basta SRB 2024}) 13... Nb4 (13... Rac8 14. Rd1 $1 Ne5 15. Nd4 $1 (15. h3 {Kukhmazov,A (2480)-Goltseva,E (2378) chess.com INT 2024} h6 $1 $11) 15... Nc6 16. a3 Nxd4 17. exd4 Bb6 18. Be3 Ng4 19. Qe4 Qxe4 20. Nxe4 Rc2 21. Rd2 Rxd2 22. Nxd2 $14 {Being a pawn up, we have a slightly better position, but Black's active bishop pair gives him good chances to hold the position.}) 14. Qb1 Bc6 (14... Nbd5 15. Bd2 Bc6 16. Qf5 $14 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf1d1] /}) 15. Qf5 $1 Rac8 (15... g6 16. Qe5 $14) 16. a3 Nbd5 17. Bd2 Nxc3 18. Bxc3 Nd5 19. Be1 $13 {According to the engine, we have a pleasant +0.25. We're playing for a minimal-risk, secure position, where it's crucial not to allow our opponent any concrete chances to equalize.}) 5. Nf3 Nc6 (5... Nf6 $6 6. Bg5 Be6 {An interesting line suggested by Jordan van Foreest in his 2023. Chessable course. I analyzed a few options here and definitely think that} 7. g3 {is the most interesting one!} (7. Bxf6 {This forced line actually represents a position that Black would be eager to jump into.} Qxf6 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Qf4 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Qe2 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Nxc5 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxc5 15. Nxe6 fxe6 $11 16. g3 {This is the end of the forced line, where we enter into an opposite-colored bishop endgame. White can try a little bit due to the weakness of e6, but objectively, it should be a draw.}) (7. e3 {The most played and most solid move. The problem for us is that after} c4 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. a3 Nc6 10. g3 Bd6 $1 {Black has a perfectly fine position, as proven by Bai Jinshi in 2023.} (10... O-O-O $6 {is a good example of how not to play this position.} 11. b3 $1 cxb3 12. Bg2 Na5 13. Nd2 Nc4 14. Rb1 b6 15. Rxb3 Kb8 16. Nxc4 dxc4 17. Rxb6+ axb6 18. Qa4 Qf5 19. Qa8+ {1-0 Cuenca Jimenez,J (2529)-Ceres,D (2434) Casablanca MAR 2023}) (10... Qd8 {is definitely the move we want to see. I'll provide a few lines and some nice ideas on how to play against it.} 11. Bg2 Be7 12. h4 h6 {[%cal Rf3g5]} (12... g6 {[%cal Yh4h5,Yg6g5]} 13. Ng1 $1 {[%cal Gg1e2,Ge2f4] Beautiful maneuver. The knight is going to f4, helping to put pressure on d5 and e6.} Bf8 14. Nge2 Bh6 15. h5 Kf8 16. hxg6 hxg6 17. Nf4 $18 {[%csl Rd5,Re6] Martirosyan,H (2632)-Nihal,S (2620) chess.com INT 2021}) (12... O-O $2 {Martirosyan,H (2632)-Nihal,S (2620) chess.com INT 2021} 13. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1h5]} Bxg5 14. hxg5 {[%cal Gh1h8]} Qxg5 15. Bxd5 {[%cal Re6d5,Rh1h5]} Rad8 16. Qh5 Qxh5 17. Rxh5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Rxd5 19. Nxd5 $16 {[%csl Rc4]}) 13. O-O O-O 14. Nh2 $5 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gf2f4] Preparing a pawn storm on the kingside.} Qa5 15. f4 f6 16. g4 Rad8 17. Qe2 $13 {White has a very interesting position, which the engine evaluates with the classic ''0.00.''}) (10... Rd8 $1 {One of Black's most solid moves. The idea is to play ...Rd7 followed by ...Qd8, securing the d5-pawn sufficiently with this "battery.} 11. Bg2 a6 12. Qa4 Rd7 {[%cal Gf6d8]} 13. O-O Qd8 14. Nd2 $13 {[%cal Gb2b3,Yg7g6,Ye3e4] White has a promising position full of ideas, but Black remains solid.}) 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O Rfd8 $1 {Precise move, leaving the f8 square for the bishop.} 13. b3 Na5 14. Nd2 Bf8 15. bxc4 dxc4 $11 {Bu Xiangzhi (2677)-Bai,J (2585) Nanjing CHN 2023}) 7... Nc6 8. Bg2 h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. O-O O-O-O (10... cxd4 11. Nb5 $1 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb5c7,Gf3d4]}) 11. Rc1 $1 {A significant improvement over previous attempts with 11.Qa4. After failing to create problems in the opening in 2023, Bu Xiangzhi found an interesting improvement that leads to exciting complications} (11. Qa4 Kb8 12. Rad1 a6 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ne1 {A clever plan by White, compelling Black to respond appropriately. The idea is twofold: White attacks the d5 pawn and prepares to transfer the knight to d3.} Bd4 15. Nd3 Rd7 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. Nf4 Qe5 18. Rfd1 Rcd8 19. e3 Ba7 20. Nce2 $14 Rd6 21. b4 Ne7 22. Nd3 $16 {Abasov,N (2677)-Andersen,M (2614) Lublin POL 2023}) 11... Kb8 12. e3 $1 g5 {Black is trying to continue with his typical plan in this line.} ({The best move was} 12... cxd4 {leading to some simplifications.} 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. exd4 $13 {[%cal Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Yf1e1,Ye1e5] According to the engine, Black's position is OK, but I like our long-term chances.}) 13. Qa4 $1 h5 (13... g4 $5 14. Nd2 $1 cxd4 15. Nb5 a6 16. Rxc6 $1 axb5 17. Qxb5 dxe3 $1 ({Bai failed to find the best defense, and after} 17... Qe7 $2 {his position crumbled very quickly.} 18. Nb3 $1 dxe3 19. Nc5 $18 {[%cal Gc5a6,Gc6b6] Bu Xiangzhi (2689)-Bai,J (2564) Fuling CHN 2024}) 18. fxe3 Qe7 19. Nb3 Qb4 20. Rb6 Qxb5 21. Rxb5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb3c5,Gb3d4,Ga2a4,Ga4a5] White has a slightly better position due to his better piece placement. Black has the bishop pair, but I don't like the bishop on e6 - it looks like a pawn.}) 14. b4 $1 {I believe this is what Xiangzhi had in his preparation when he entered the Tarrasch again against Bai. The fire starts, and Black needs to be careful to survive!} cxb4 (14... g4 15. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. Nb5 a6 18. bxc5 $36 {[%cal Gc5c6] }) 15. Nb5 Qe7 (15... a6 16. Rxc6 $18) 16. Ne5 Rc8 17. e4 $3 {An amazing move! Our light-squared bishop is definitely eager to join the action!} a6 (17... dxe4 18. Bxe4 $18) 18. Nxc6+ bxc6 (18... Rxc6 19. Rxc6 bxc6 20. Nc3 Qb7 21. Rb1 $36 {}) 19. Nc3 Qb7 $1 {A strong move, but also purely defensive. For now, the queen is keeping everything together.} (19... bxc3 $4 20. Rxc3 $18 {[%cal Gf1b1]}) 20. a3 $36 {[%csl Rb8] The position looks very pleasant for White. With 14.b4!, we have a new position, and Black must have strong nerves to survive in a position with the exposed king on b8.} (20. Rb1 dxe4 21. Nxe4 Qb5 22. Qc2 {[%cal Gf1c1,Ge4c5,Gg2f1] is a good alternative for White.})) 6. dxc5 d4 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 $5 (10. Rc1 Qb6 11. e3 Nf6 12. Bc4 dxe3 13. Bxe3 Qb4+ 14. Kf1 $5 {It is the line we can find in the previous chapter.}) 10... Qf5 {Engine's favorite move. Here, the queen can be much more active than on b6.} (10... Nxb4 11. Rc1 Qd6 12. e3 Ne7 $1 (12... Nc6 $6 {is the most played move, but Black has better options.} 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bc3 Ne7 15. Bxd4 $1 O-O 16. Bc5 Qf6 (16... Qxd1+ 17. Rxd1 $18) 17. Bd3 Be6 18. O-O Rfd8 19. Bd4 $14 {[%csl Gd3,Gd4][%cal Gc1c5,Gd1e2]}) (12... dxe3 $6 13. Bc3 $1 Qxd1+ 14. Kxd1 {[%cal Gc3b4,Gc3g7]} Nxa2 15. Bxg7 Nxc1 16. Kxc1 $14) 13. Nxd4 O-O (13... a6 $6 14. Be2 O-O 15. O-O Nbc6 16. Bc3 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 $16 {[%cal Gd4c5,Gd1b3] Sturua,Z (2531)-Grabuzova,T (2323) Rhodes GRE 2019}) (13... Nbc6 $6 14. Nb5 $1 Qd8 15. Bc3 O-O 16. Bc4 $14 a6 17. Nd6 $16 {Herrera,M (2081)-Barrionuevo,P (2187) Buenos Aires ARG 2024}) 14. Bc4 {seems like the most natural move. White will aim to use the bishop pair to gain an advantage.} (14. Nb5 $5 {I also like this forced, unpleasant line for Black.} Nd3+ 15. Bxd3 Qxd3 16. Nc7 Qg6 $1 (16... Rb8 $2 17. Bb4 Qe4 18. Qd4 Qxg2 19. Bxe7 Qxh1+ 20. Kd2 Qg2 21. Bxf8 $16) 17. O-O Bh3 18. Qf3 Bg4 19. Qf4 {Critical moment for Black. The only move to maintain equality is} (19. Qg3 Rac8 20. Bb4 Qe4 21. Qf4 Qxf4 22. exf4 Rfd8 23. Bxe7 Rd7 24. Nb5 Rxc1 25. Rxc1 Rxe7 26. f3 Be6 27. Nxa7 h5 $11 {Black should hold the draw.}) 19... Rad8 $1 (19... Rac8 $2 20. Bb4 $1 Rxc7 21. Qxc7 Nd5 22. Qd6 Nxb4 23. Qxb4 $18 {Navrotescu,A (2275)-Hund,S (2076) Corte FRA 2022}) 20. Bb4 Rd7 21. f3 Bh3 22. Qg3 Qxg3 23. hxg3 Rc8 24. Nb5 Be6 25. Bxe7 Rxc1 26. Rxc1 Rxe7 27. Nxa7 Kf8 28. Nc8 Rd7 29. a4 $11) (14. Be2 a5 $1 15. Rc4 b5 16. Bxb4 axb4 17. Nxb5 Qxd1+ 18. Bxd1 Rxa2 19. Rxb4 Ba6 $11) 14... Nbc6 (14... a6 15. O-O b5 16. Bxb5 Nxa2 17. Bc6 Rb8 18. Rc2 Nb4 19. Bxb4 Rxb4 20. Bf3 Bb7 21. Nc6 $18 {Bluebaum,M (2647)-Raahul,V (2314) chess.com INT 2024}) 15. Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Bc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4]} Qg6 17. O-O Rd8 (17... Bh3 {is the best way to play for Black, but it carries no risk for White.} 18. Bd5 Rad8 19. Qb3 $13 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gg1h1]}) 18. Qb3 Rb8 19. Rfd1 Be6 {Kantor,G (2506)-Kosic,D (2493) Budapest HUN 2017} (19... Bf5 20. Rxd8+ Nxd8 21. Be2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) 20. Rxd8+ $1 Nxd8 21. Qb5 $3 {[%cal Gb5e8]} Nc6 22. Bd3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3]} a6 23. Qb1 Qh5 24. a4 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3]}) (10... Qb6 {Quite a boring move, but the engine proves that Black has solid chances for equality.} 11. Qa4 a6 (11... Nf6 $2 12. b5 Ne7 13. Ba5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} Qe6 14. Nxd4 $16 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gf1e2]}) 12. e3 dxe3 13. fxe3 Rb8 $1 {Played by LCZero a few months ago.} (13... Bd7 $2 14. b5 Nce7 (14... Nd8 $2 15. Qa3 $1 Ne7 {Demuth,A (2517)-Leconte,M (2246) Brest FRA 2019} 16. Rd1 $1 $18 {[%cal Gd2a5]}) 15. Qa3 $1 $146 Nf6 (15... Bxb5 $2 16. Nd4 $1 Bxf1 17. Rxf1 $16 {[%cal Gd2a5,Ga1d1]}) 16. Bc4 $1 {[%cal Gf3e5]} Be6 17. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gb5a6,Ge1g1,Gd2a5,Gf3g5] /}) 14. b5 axb5 15. Qxb5 (15. Bxb5 Nge7 16. Qb4 Bd7 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Qxb6 Rxb6 19. a4 c5 {Here, we have the chance to see a perfect game by 3600+ engine.} 20. a5 Rb5 21. O-O f6 22. e4 O-O 23. Rfb1 Ra8 24. Rxb5 Bxb5 25. Rc1 Bc6 26. Rxc5 Bxe4 $11 {Stockfish dev-20240728-2343f7 (3662)-LCZero 0.31-dag-5350a2e-BT4-6 (3631) tcec-chess.com INT 2024.}) 15... Qxb5 16. Bxb5 Nf6 {Tan,Z (2526)-Lei,T (2545) Chongqing CHN 2023} (16... Bd7 17. O-O {[%cal Ga2a4,Gf1c1] would transpose to the main line.}) 17. O-O O-O 18. Rfc1 Bd7 19. a4 $13 {[%csl Gb5,Yb7,Gd2,Ye3][%cal Ga4a5,Gc1b1] The position is close to equal, but I still believe in the bishop pair!}) 11. g4 $5 {An interesting move, seen in only one game, definitely creates excitement on the board. What I really love about this aggressive push is that Black has only one move to fight for equality.} (11. Rc1 {The move played by ex-World Champion Ding Liren. The idea is to play Rc5, followed by b5.} Nf6 12. Rc5 Qe6 $1 {A strong improvement over the previous game.} (12... Qd7 13. b5 Nd8 14. Bb4 (14. Rc4 $1 {is a slightly more precise move order.} Ne6 15. Bb4) 14... Ne6 15. Rc4 Nd5 16. Nxd4 Nxb4 17. Rxb4 O-O 18. e3 Qe7 (18... Rd8 $1 {[%cal Rd8d1]} 19. Be2 Qd5 20. O-O Qxa2 21. h4 $13 {[%cal Ga7a5] The final position is quite unclear. White holds a slight advantage of 0.20, which is generally considered pleasant, but Black should be able to hold on and is likely fine with accurate play.}) 19. Qd2 $14 {Ding Liren (2799)-Bai,J (2593) Hangzhou CHN 2022}) 13. b5 Ne4 14. Rc1 Ne5 $11 {Black's position looks absolutely fine without any problems.}) 11... Qe4 $1 {It seems that this move is Black's only chance to fight for equality. Any other queen retreat will result in a huge advantage for White.} (11... Qf6 $6 12. g5 $1 Qf5 13. Bg2 a6 14. O-O Nge7 15. a4 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Gg2][%cal Gd1b1,Gf1c1] /}) (11... Qe6 $5 12. b5 $1 {An energetic improvement over the previous game.} (12. Qb3 {was played in only one OTB game, where Black failed to claim equality after Black failed to claim equality after.} a6 $1 $11 (12... Nf6 $6 13. b5 Ne7 14. Qxe6 Bxe6 15. Nxd4 Bxg4 16. Bg2 $16 {[%csl Gd2,Gg2] Ongut,T (2281)-Gueci,T (2243) Budapest HUN 2022})) 12... Ne5 13. Bg2 Qxg4 14. O-O $1 Ng6 (14... Nxf3+ 15. exf3 Qg6 16. Re1+ Be6 17. f4 $18 {[%csl Rd4,Re8][%cal Gd2b4] Bb4 is coming. There are also possible Qa4 and f5 threats in the air. Black's position is completely lost.}) 15. Bc1 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} N8e7 16. Qxd4 $16 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2] If Black trades queens, the bishop on g2 will be fatal for the undeveloped queenside. On the other hand, if Black avoids the trade with 16...Qh5, 17.Bb2 will weaken the kingside structure, creating a threat to g7.}) (11... Qg6 12. b5 Nce7 13. Rg1 $16 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf3e5,Gf2f4] Ne5 followed by f4 is a huge threat. Black won't be able to handle all these threats simultaneously.}) (11... Qd5 {seems like the most natural square to retreat the queen. We claim a big advantage after} 12. Qb3 $1 Be6 (12... Qxb3 13. axb3 Bxg4 14. Bg2 $16 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb4b5]}) 13. b5 Nce7 14. Qxd5 Bxd5 15. Rg1 $16 {[%csl Gd2,Rd4,Gf1] White has a dominant position.}) 12. Qb1 $5 (12. Bg2 {could be an interesting alternative} Bxg4 (12... d3 $6 13. Bc3 $1 dxe2 14. Qxe2 Qxe2+ 15. Kxe2 Nge7 16. b5 Nd5 17. Bxg7 Rg8 18. Bh6 Rxg4 19. Rhe1 Nce7 20. Kf1 Bd7 21. Rab1 $13 {[%cal Gf3e5]}) 13. b5 Nce7 (13... Ne5 14. Nh4 $1 (14. O-O Ne7 15. Qa4 O-O 16. Nxd4 Qg6 17. Kh1 $13 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge2e4] The position remains close to equal, but White has the bishop pair in an open position and therefore holds better chances.}) 14... Nd3+ 15. Kf1 Qe7 16. Nf3 Nc5 17. Bb4 Rd8 18. Rc1 b6 19. Nxd4 Qe5 20. Bc6+ Ke7 21. Bc3 {[%csl Re7,Yg8,Yh8][%cal Gh1g1] The position remains tense, but I believe White's chances are significantly better.}) 14. Qb3 {[%cal Gd2b4,Gb3f7]} Be6 $1 {With this great defensive move, Black can achieve equality without problems.} (14... Nf6 $2 15. Qxf7+ Kxf7 16. Ng5+ Ke8 17. Nxe4 $18 {[%csl Gg2]}) 15. Qa4 Nf6 16. Qxd4 O-O 17. Bb4 Rfe8 18. Qxe4 Nxe4 $11 {[%cal Ge7d5]}) 12... d3 $5 (12... Qxb1+ 13. Rxb1 Bxg4 14. Bg2 a6 15. a4 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5e4] Necessary maneuver to neutralize the power of the g2 bishop.} 16. Rc1 Be4 $1 17. Rg1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb4b5]} Rd8 18. Bh3 {Critical moment for Black. Instead of passive play, his best chance is to continue with active play!} (18. b5 axb5 19. axb5 Nce7 20. Bh3 {[%cal Gd2b4]} Bf5 21. Bxf5 Nxf5 22. Rg4 Nf6 23. Rf4 Ne7 24. Rxd4 Rxd4 25. Nxd4 Kd7 $11) 18... Nge7 (18... Bg6 $2 19. Rg5 $1 f6 20. Rgc5 $18 {[%cal Gb4b5]}) (18... d3 {also seems okay for Black. The position is around equal, but still contains a lot of venom.} 19. Rg3 Nf6 (19... dxe2 20. Ng5 Bd3 21. Rc5 $1 $16 {[%cal Gg3e3]}) 20. b5 axb5 21. axb5 Ne7 22. Ne5 $13 {[%cal Ge5d3]}) 19. Rxg7 $13 {[%csl Gd2,Re8,Gh3][%cal Gb4b5] The position remains complex, with both possible outcomes.}) 13. b5 Ne5 (13... Nd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 (14... Qxh1 $2 15. Qxd3 Bxg4 16. Bb4 Ne7 17. Rd1 $18) 15. e3 Qxg4 (15... Qd5 16. Rg1 $16 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gg4g5]}) 16. h3 Qe4 17. Rg1 {Very interesting position for both sides, with only one difference: Black must be much more careful and precise than us.} (17. Qb2 Qxh1 18. Qxg7 Bxh3 19. Qe5+ Kd7 20. Qd4+ $11) 17... Qe5 18. Qc1 Nf6 19. Qc3 (19. Bc3 Qh2 20. Rg2 Qh1 21. Qb2 Bxh3 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. Qxf6 Bxg2 24. Qxh8+ Kd7 25. Qd4+ Ke7 26. Qe5+ $11) 19... Qxc3 20. Bxc3 Ne4 21. Bd4 d2+ 22. Ke2 Bd7 23. Kf3 f5 24. Rxg7 Rc8 25. Bd3 Be6 (25... Rc1 26. Rg1 Rxa1 27. Bxa1 $14 {[%cal Gf3e2] /}) 26. Rd1 Rc1 27. Rgg1 Rxd1 28. Rxd1 {[%cal Gf3e2] The position is approximately equal, but Black still needs to play a few more precise moves to maintain equality.}) 14. Nxe5 Qxh1 (14... Qxe5 15. f4 Qd5 16. Rg1 dxe2 17. Bg2 Qd8 18. Qe4+ (18. f5 $13 {[%csl Gd2,Gg2][%cal Gb1b2,Gb2g7]}) 18... Ne7 19. Bb4 $13 {[%cal Ga1c1,Ge4e5] I'm not sure if it is now possible to find the only moves to save the position, but I believe White has much better chances in practice.}) 15. Qxd3 Be6 (15... Ne7 $5 16. Bb4 Qd5 17. Qc3 {[%cal Ga1d1] It already looks like a dangerous position for Black.} Be6 18. Qc7 O-O {A brave piece sacrifice by Black, but it's not easy to prove compensation.} 19. Bxe7 Rfe8 20. Ba3 Rac8 21. Qd6 Qxb5 22. e3 Qa5+ 23. Bb4 Qa4 24. Bd2 $13 {[%cal Yf7f6,Ye5f3,Yf3d4]}) 16. b6 {After this move, the fire starts on the board, and Black needs to play more than 10 precise moves to survive.} Ne7 (16... a6 17. Rd1 $16) 17. Qb5+ Nc6 18. f3 {[%csl Rh1]} (18. Nxc6 $5 Qxc6 19. Qxc6+ bxc6 20. Bg2 Kd7 21. Rc1 Bd5 22. Bxd5 cxd5 23. Rc7+ Kd8 24. Rxf7 axb6 25. Rxg7 Rxa2 26. Be3 {The result leads to an interesting position, but I believe Black wouldn't have a big problem saving it.}) 18... a6 (18... O-O {It looks like a human move, but if Black is not careful, his queen could get trapped on h1.} 19. Nxc6 Qxh2 (19... bxc6 20. Qe5 $3 {[%csl Rh1,Gh2]} Bxg4 21. Bc3 f6 22. Qg3 $18 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Ge1f2,Gf1h3]}) 20. Nd4 Qg3+ 21. Kd1 axb6 (21... Rfd8 22. e3 axb6 23. Kc2 Rac8+ 24. Kb2 {In this version, we have already reached a safe square for our king and are ready to bring our pieces into the game. If 24...h5 is the only move for equality, I wouldn't mind playing it.}) 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. Qb3 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c2,Yd1c1,Yc1b1] Objectively, the position is equal but very interesting for both sides. Black will play actively, but if we manage to get our king to b1, anything is possible.}) 19. Qc5 Ne7 (19... Rc8 $5 20. Nxc6 Rxc6 21. Qe5 O-O 22. Kf2 f6 23. Qg3 Rc2 24. Re1 Rxd2 25. Bg2 Qxe1+ 26. Kxe1 $13 {[%cal Gg3d6,Gd6c7]}) 20. Bb4 Nd5 21. Nc4 Qxh2 22. Nd6+ Kf8 23. e4 Qh4+ 24. Ke2 Nf4+ 25. Ke3 {We've already moved beyond human chess. This is where the real fun begins. I want to show you the crazy line Black needs to find to maintain equality.} Kg8 $1 26. Kxf4 h5 $1 27. Ke3 (27. Nf5 Bxf5 28. Qxf5 Qh2+ 29. Ke3 Qg1+ $11) 27... hxg4 28. Qe5 $13 {[%cal Gb4c3,Ge5f4] The position is equal, but a draw is far away. The conclusion is that after 11.g4!?, we have a new, unexplored variation that could be a deadly weapon, especially if you surprise your opponent. 11.Rc1 is always a great, healthy alternative.} *

