{[%evp 0,6,18,18,20,1,5,5,22]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 (5. Qb3 $5 {is also an interesting move, putting pressure on the d5 pawn and potentially disrupting Black's coordination.} c5 $1 {Thanks to this move, Black solves his problem very quickly, improving his position and neutralizing White's pressure.} 6. Nxd5 Nc6 7. Bg5 $5 {This is a relatively new idea, and it can definitely be tried in at least one game. If Black doesn’t find the crucial 8...c4!!, he could find himself in serious trouble.} Nge7 (7... f6 $6 8. Be3 cxd4 9. Bd2 Na5 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. e4 dxe3 12. Nxe3 $14 Bc5 $1 (12... Qd4 13. Qb3 Bb4 {Romanov,E (2593)-Boyer,M (2418) Rochefort FRA 2024} 14. O-O-O $1 $16) 13. Rc1 Ba7 14. Nf3 Nge7 15. Qb3 {[%cal Re8g8]} Qb6 16. Bc4 Qxb3 17. Bxb3 $13) 8. Nb6 c4 $1 {A fine sacrifice of a pawn!!} 9. Nxc4 b5 10. e4 $5 {It's hard to understand what is happening here, but the engine claims equality with the calm} Qxd4 $1 (10... bxc4 $2 11. Bxc4 $18) (10... Nxd4 {is also enough for equality.} 11. Qc3 f6 (11... bxc4 12. Rd1 $1 $16 (12. O-O-O Nd5 $1 $132)) 12. Be3 Nec6 13. O-O-O Bb4 14. Rxd4 Qc7 $3 (14... Nxd4 15. Qxb4 $1 bxc4 16. Ne2 Nc6 17. Qxc4 Ne5 18. Qd5 $14 {/}) 15. Qc2 Nxd4 {½-½ Fier,A (2600)-Basso,P (2516) Lorca ESP 2022}) 11. Nd2 Be6 12. Qc3 Qxc3 13. bxc3 Ng6 $11 {[%csl Ya2,Yc3]}) ({We can always play} 5. Bf4 {here and try the same ideas we saw in Chapter 3.} c6 6. e3 Nf6 (6... Bd6 7. Qf3 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gf1d3,Gg1e2]}) 7. h3 $5 (7. Bd3 Bd6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. h3 Re8 10. O-O $14 Qc7 11. Qd2 Nbd7 (11... Be6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Ne5 $14) 12. Rac1 $13) 7... Bd6 8. Qf3 $13 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g4]}) 5... Nf6 (5... c6 {The second most popular move, and quite solid.} 6. e4 $5 dxe4 7. Ng5 Be7 8. Bc4 Nh6 $6 {Most of the players in the database went for this move, even though having the knight on the edge of the board can be a little bit unpleasant for Black. Unfortunately for us, it's the most precise move to maintain equality.} (8... Bxg5 {This is definitely the continuation we want. The arising positions are very aggressive and unclear.} 9. Qh5 Be7 (9... g6 $6 10. Qxg5 Qxg5 11. Bxg5 $16 Bf5 12. O-O $1 h6 {Shpanko,N (2177)-Lehaci,M (2225) Budva MNE 2023} (12... Nd7 13. Rae1 $16 {[%csl Re4]}) 13. Bf4 $1 Nd7 14. Rae1 $16 {[%cal Gc3e4]}) 10. Qxf7+ Kd7 11. Na4 $5 $36 {Definitely one of the most interesting continuations in this position. The arising positions are very unclear and offer interesting chances for both sides.} (11. Be6+ $5 Kc7 12. Bf4+ Kb6 13. Bxc8 {According to the engine, 13.d5 is a more precise move, but I believe that after trading the bishop, d5 can be much harder to handle in practice.} (13. d5 Bxe6 14. Qxe6 Bg5 $1 15. Bd6 (15. dxc6 Nxc6 (15... Bxf4 $5 16. c7+ Kxc7 17. Nd5+ Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Nf6 19. Qf7+ Nbd7 $13) 16. Nd5+ Ka7 17. Bc7 Qf8 18. Bb6+ Kb8 19. Bc7+ Ka7 20. Bb6+ {Hakobyan,A (2497)-Khalifman,A (2614) Batumi GEO 2018}) 15... Be7 $11) 13... Qxc8 14. d5 $36 {The position is so aggressive that Black must play some serious defensive moves; otherwise, he will lose easily, as happened in the following game.} c5 $2 (14... Ka7 $1 15. Be3+ c5 16. b4 Nd7 17. O-O Qf8 18. Qe6 Ngf6 19. d6 Bxd6 20. Rfd1 $13 {With mutual chances.}) 15. a4 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd5d6]} e3 (15... Qg4 16. b4 $1 Qg6 17. bxc5+ Kxc5 18. Qxg6 hxg6 19. Rc1 $18 {[%cal Gc3b5,Ge1g1]}) 16. O-O $1 Nd7 17. Qe6+ Ka5 18. Bxe3 c4 19. d6 Bxd6 20. Qxd6 Qc6 21. Qd2 {1-0 Predke,A (2692)-Indjic,A (2613) Dubai UAE 2022}) ({Another interesting move could be} 11. Bf4 {but unfortunately, at the end of the line, we don't have anything better than repeating moves.} Qf8 12. Qe6+ Kd8 13. Qe5 Nd7 14. Qc7+ Ke8 15. Nxe4 Bd8 16. Nd6+ Ke7 17. Bg5+ Ngf6 18. Nf5+ Ke8 19. Nd6+ Ke7 20. Nf5+ Ke8 21. Nd6+ {½-½ (21) Koelle,T (2312)-Stern,R (2517) Magdeburg GER 2021}) 11... Qa5+ (11... b5 12. Bf4 $1 $18 {[%cal Ga4b6,Gc4e6]}) 12. Bd2 Qxa4 13. b3 Qa3 14. Qxg7 Nf6 15. Qxh8 Qd6 16. g3 b5 17. Bf1 $1 {[%cal Gf1h3] The position is unclear. Black has two pieces for the rook, but his king is still in the center, and the queenside is completely undeveloped.} ({With} 17. Bf4 {we always have a draw in the pocket.} Qb4+ 18. Bd2 {½-½ Anton Guijarro,D (2688)-Vallejo Pons,F (2710) Linares ESP 2020}) 17... Qe6 $1 18. h4 {[%cal Gf1h3]} Kc7 $1 (18... Qg8 {Good idea, but the wrong move order. After} 19. Qxg8 Nxg8 {We immediately advance with our kingside majority and take advantage of the fact that the king is still on d7 (the g4 square is not protected).} 20. g4 $1 (20. Bh3+ Kc7 21. Bxc8 Kxc8 22. g4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge1f1,Ga1e1] According to the engine, the position is equal, but I like our chances. We'll continue with Kf1-Re1, aiming to capture the e4 pawn. After that, we'll keep our kingside majority (3 vs 1), which will be uncomfortable for Black.} a5 $1 (22... Bf6 {Basso,P (2551)-Kambrath,Y (2397) Cattolica ITA 2021. This move shows how easy it is to make a mistake here. The d4 pawn is not important for us. We want to exploit Black's weak development and push our kingside majority} 23. O-O-O $3 Ra7 (23... Bxd4 24. Rhe1 $18) 24. g5 $1 Bxd4 25. Rhe1 $16 {[%csl Rb8,Rg8][%cal Ge1e4,Gh4h5]}) 23. Kf1 Na6 24. Re1 Bb4 25. Bxb4 Nxb4 26. Rxe4 Kd7 27. Rf4 $13 {[%cal Gf4f7,Gg4g5,Gf1g2,Gh1e1,Gh4h5]}) 20... Kc7 21. g5 Bd6 22. Bh3 Nd7 $1 (22... Bxh3 $2 {This move is clearly not in Black's interest. After} 23. Rxh3 Nd7 24. Kf1 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gh4h5] the e4 pawn becomes a clear target, and h5 followed by Kg3-Kg4! is also looming.}) 23. Kf1 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gh4h5,Gf1g2] Very soon, we'll transpose into an interesting endgame. I'm not sure if Black will be able to hold the kingside majority, but I believe we have a slightly better position.}) 19. Bh3 Qg8 20. Qxg8 Nxg8 21. Bxc8 Kxc8 22. g4 $13 {[%cal Ge1f1,Ga1e1] The position is roughly equal. If Black manages to find some quick counterplay on the queenside, he should be fine. Otherwise, as we saw in the game Basso - Kambrath, the position can quickly turn in White's favor.}) 9. Ncxe4 (9. Ngxe4 {[%cal Gc1h6]} Nf5 10. d5 O-O 11. Bf4 cxd5 12. Nxd5 Nc6 13. O-O Be6 $11) 9... Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6] Almost everyone played short castle here, but that's a mistake. Black should first take care of the d5 square.} (9... O-O 10. O-O Bf5 (10... Nd7 $2 11. Qd3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rh7] Samunenkov,I (2535)-Ratkovic,M (2489) chess.com INT 2024}) 11. h3 $1 Bg6 (11... Bxe4 $2 12. Nxe4 Nf5 13. Qg4 $1 g6 {Ouellet,M (2280)-Sriniaiyer,S (2118) Dulles USA 2024} 14. Ng3 $1 Nxg3 15. fxg3 $1 {[%csl Gc1,Gc4,Rf7][%cal Gc1h6]} Kg7 16. Qf4 $16 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ga1d1,Gd4d5]}) 12. g4 $3 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gf2f4]}) 10. O-O Nb6 11. Bb3 Nd5 (11... O-O 12. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Rh7]} Bf5 13. Nf3 Ng4 14. h3 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf6 16. Qd3 Nbd5 17. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Gc1][%cal Gf1e1,Gc1g5]}) 12. Qd3 Nf5 (12... O-O 13. Nxh7 $16) 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Rfe1 $13 {According to the engine, Black's position is OK, but I like our long-term chances.}) (5... h6 $6 6. Bf4 (6. Ne5 $5 {Attempt to play aggressively!} Nf6 7. e4 Be6 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Bc4 Nc6 $1 {A novelty and the only move to maintain equality, which means there's no harm in trying this line in an OTB game.} (9... Nxc3 $6 10. bxc3 Bxc4 11. Nxc4 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4][%cal Gc4e3,Ge3f5,Gd1g4]} Qd5 12. Ne3 Qe4 (12... Qc6 $2 13. O-O Nd7 14. Rb1 O-O-O 15. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Gb1,Gb3,Rf7][%cal Gb3b7] Raja,R (2514)-Eliseev,S (2276) Fagernes NOR 2024}) 13. O-O Bd6 14. Qh5 $5 Nc6 15. Nf5 $36 {[%cal Gf5d6,Gc1a3] . We have a slightly better position, but what I really like about 6. Ne5!? and this whole line is how aggressive and dangerous it looks. It's not easy for Black to find all these engine moves, especially since it’s a rare line with only a few games in the database.}) (9... c6 $2 {Urazayev,A (2460)-Rakhmanov,A (2632) Astana KAZ 2023}) 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qa4 Qd7 12. O-O $13 {[%csl Ya6,Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gf1e1] White gets a risk-free position, but Black remains solid.}) 6... Nf6 (6... c6 7. e4 $1 $146 {There’s no time for hesitation. Once again, we’re aiming for maximum aggression, looking to seize the initiative and put pressure on the opponent immediately.} dxe4 8. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Gf1c4]} Be6 9. Bc4 Bxc4 10. Nxc4 Nf6 11. Qb3 b5 12. Ne5 Ra7 13. O-O $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Re8][%cal Ga1e1,Gc3e4] /.}) 7. e3 Bd6 8. Be5 $1 (8. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11) 8... c6 9. Bd3 {This move will slowly postpone Black's development since ...Nbd7 is not possible. Of course, Black can capture with ..Bxe5 at any moment, but after dxe5, there won’t be a good square for the knight on f6.} O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. h3 $5 {[%cal Rc8g4]} ({Two young GMs went for the interesting move} 11. Bxf6 $5 Qxf6 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Qd8 14. Qb3 {And the position seems indeed unpleasant for Black. Both of their opponents failed to find the energetic} b5 $1 $13 (14... Re7 {[%csl Gb7]} 15. Rae1 $1 Be6 16. Bc4 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 $14 b5 18. Qc3 $16 {[%cal Gf3e5] Petrov,N (2551)-Galyas,M (2467) Durres ALB 2023})) (11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. h3 Nbd7 13. Qc2 $14) 11... Bxe5 12. Nxe5 c5 13. Rc1 Qd6 (13... c4 $2 14. Bb1 b5 15. a3 $1 $16 {[%cal Rb5b4,Gf2f4,Gg2g4,Gd1f3]} (15. f4 $40 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gg2g4] Cheng,B (2547)-Rishi,S (2461) Canberra AUS 2022. It's definitely the idea we want to follow, but there's no reason to allow 15...b4.})) 14. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3g3] Only active moves count!} Be6 15. Qg3 cxd4 (15... Nc6 $6 16. Nxc6 Qxg3 17. fxg3 bxc6 18. dxc5 $14 {[%csl Ya6,Yc6][%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4]}) 16. exd4 Nbd7 ({According to the engine, Black's best move was} 16... Nc6 {leading to an endgame where White has slightly better chances thanks to Black's weak queenside structure.} 17. Nxc6 Qxg3 18. fxg3 bxc6 19. Na4 $13 {[%csl Ya6,Yc6]}) 17. f4 $14 Ne4 $2 {Vrolijk,L (2473)-Fataliyeva,U (2324) Sitges ESP 2021. Unfortunately for Vrolijk, he didn't manage to find the next two amazing moves:} 18. Bxe4 $1 dxe4 19. d5 $3 Bf5 20. Nc4 Qf6 21. d6 $16 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc4e3,Gc1d1] With a dominant position! The knights are controlling the whole board, while the d6 pawn is a huge threat for Black.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. Bxf6 (7. e3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 $14) 7... Qxf6 8. Qb3 Ra7 $1 (8... b5 $2 {A mistake played in more than 50 games, including by quite strong players and GMs!} 9. a4 b4 10. Nxd5 $1 Qd8 11. e4 $1 c6 12. Qe3 cxd5 13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Rc1 Be7 15. Bd3 {After this move, we have a winning position. I'll provide an analysis of the seven most played responses.} Ra7 {The most logical defense. The problem for Black is that after} (15... Qd8 {Besides 15...Ra7, the most logical move to be expected, after} 16. Be4 Nd7 {we continue with our greatest weapon} 17. d5 $1 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 Rc8 19. Rxc8 $1 Qxc8 20. O-O $1 (20. Ng5 {is also fine for us.} O-O {Santryan,D (2167)-Garayev,K (2341) Bratislava SVK 2019} 21. Nxf7 Qc5 22. Qxc5 Nxc5 23. Ne5+ Kh8 24. b3 $16) 20... Qc5 21. Qd2 O-O 22. Rc1 Qa7 23. g3 $18 {[%csl Gc1,Gd5] Same material, but a completely lost position for Black. The c-file and the incredibly important bishop on d5 give us all we need. Black is essentially paralyzed, and it's difficult for him to find any counterplay.}) (15... Qd7 16. Be4 Ra7 17. d5 {As we already saw, d5 is our most important weapon to win the piece back, break Black's pawn structure, and gain the initiative.} Bxd5 18. Ne5 $1 Qd6 19. Bxd5 Qxd5 20. Rc8+ Bd8 21. Nc6+ $18 {[%csl Ra7,Rb8,Rd8,Ge3] Parligras,M (2591)-Thorfinnsson,B (2439) Reykjavik ISL 2021}) (15... Qb7 {One of the most logical moves. Black simply aims to defend the rook with ...Qa7.} 16. Be4 Qa7 17. Qf4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] An important move to remember! We step off the diagonal, avoid trading queens, and threaten d5.} Nd7 18. d5 O-O 19. Rc7 $1 {7th rank, half of the game! Bishop will not escape..} (19. dxe6 fxe6 20. Qg4 Nc5 21. O-O $16 {[%csl Re6] Dardha,D (2613)-Georgiev,K (2546) Israel ISR 2023}) 19... Qb6 20. dxe6 fxe6 21. Qg3 $18 {[%csl Gc7,Yd7,Re6,Ye7,Gg3][%cal Gc7b7,Gc7c6,Ge1g1]}) (15... Qd6 16. Be4 Ra7 17. d5 Rc7 (17... Rd7 18. dxe6 fxe6 19. O-O (19. Ke2 $1 O-O 20. Rhd1 $18) 19... O-O 20. Bc2 Bf6 21. Bb3 Kh8 22. Rcd1 Qe7 23. Ne5 $18 {Butvilas,A (2116)-Chatzieleftheriou,A (2258) Corum TUR 2019}) 18. Rxc7 Qxc7 19. dxe6 fxe6 20. O-O O-O 21. Qb3 $18 {Basso,P (2552)-Miletic,V (2254) Niksic MNE 2021}) (15... Qb3 16. d5 $1 {The king is in the center - let's open the position!} Qxd5 (16... Bd7 17. O-O {[%cal Re8g8,Rd3h7]} g6 18. Nd4 Qxb2 19. d6 $18 {Szeberenyi,A (2372)-Palczert,M (2264) Balatonlelle HUN 2020}) 17. Be4 Qa5 18. Bxa8 (18. O-O $1 $18) 18... b3+ 19. Nd2 O-O 20. O-O Nd7 21. Bc6 $18 {Krysa,L (2531)-Tristan,L (2535) chess24.com INT 2020}) (15... O-O {The easiest move for us. We simply took the rook with no compensation from Black.} 16. Be4 Qa5 17. Bxa8 b3+ 18. Kf1 $18 {Suleymenov,A (2418)-Aleksandrov,A (2502) Chelyabinsk RUS 2022}) 16. Be4 Qb3 {we have the stunning resource} 17. Rc8+ $3 Bd8 18. Rxb8 O-O 19. O-O {We win the piece back, are a pawn up, and have a strong passed d-pawn. The rest is just a matter of technique.} Be7 (19... Qxe3 20. fxe3 Be7 21. Rxf8+ Kxf8 {Sankalp,G (2369)-Avila Pavas,S (2406) Mumbai IND 2019} 22. d5 Bd7 23. b3 $18 {[%cal Gg1f2,Gf2e2,Gf3e5,Gf1c1]}) 20. Rxf8+ Bxf8 {Akbas,U (2387)-Pacher,M (2407) Budapest HUN 2022. As we will see in almost every line, the key idea for us is} 21. d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} Qxe3 22. fxe3 Bd7 23. b3 $18 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf3e5,Gf3d2,Gd2c4]}) (8... b6 $6 9. g3 Qd8 $6 {So far, the most played move. Here, we can continue with two good moves, although I prefer} (9... Bd6 $1 {A little bit more precise move order for Black.} 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O {[%csl Rd5]} Qd8 12. Qc2 $1 (12. Rad1 Nd7 13. Qc2 Rc8 $132 {[%cal Gd6b4]} (13... g6 $2 {Livaic,L (2543)-Valkova,A (2035) Zagreb CRO 2023} 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nf6 16. Ne5 $14 {/}) 14. e4 {Here, I'll just show the difference between Rad1 and Rfd1.} dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nf6 16. Ne5 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Qf6 18. Bxh7+ Kh8 19. Be4 c5 20. d5 Bh3 $1 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Gh3f1]}) 12... Nd7 13. Rfd1 Rc8 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 $14 {[%cal Gc2a4,Gd4d5,Ye6f5,Yf3h4]} Nf6 16. Ne5 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Qf6 18. Bxh7+ Kh8 19. Be4 c5 20. d5 $16 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Re6h3,Rh3f1] And now we see this difference, and how deep 13. Rfd1 is!}) 10. Ne5 $1 (10. h4 $1 {[%cal Gf3g5] A great alternative to 10. Ne5.} Be7 (10... h6 11. Ne5 $16 {[%cal Gf1g2,Yb3a4]}) 11. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 12. hxg5 Qxg5 (12... Nc6) 13. Bg2 c6 (13... O-O $2 14. Nxd5 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Gg2][%cal Gb3c2,Gb3e3]}) 14. Qxb6 O-O 15. Qb7 Nd7 16. Qxc6 $14 {Quintiliano Pinto,R (2509)-Languidey,S (2409) Osasco BRA 2022. I don't believe Black has sufficient compensation, as Quintiliano proved in his game.}) 10... Bd6 11. Qa4+ Nd7 {Sarkar,J (2373)-Nestorovic,N (2469) New York USA 2020} 12. Nc6 $1 b5 13. Nxd8 bxa4 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Nxa4 c5 16. e4 $1 {The point of the whole variation!} dxe4 (16... cxd4 $2 17. exd5 $1 e5 18. Rc1 $18 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1g2,Gc1c6]}) 17. O-O-O $1 $14 {[%csl Ya6,Yc5,Ye4][%cal Gd4d5] /. d5 is coming. The endgame will be terrible for Black due to his weak structure. We have a "pleasant +0.55" advantage.}) 9. a3 {[%cal Gb3c2,Rf8b4]} (9. Nxd5 $5 {An interesting move, played a few times. Generally, it might be good for one game as a surprise, but no more than that!} Qd8 10. e4 c6 11. Qb6 cxd5 12. Qxa7 Bb4+ {Black's most common continuation.} (12... dxe4 $1 {Most accurate move, played in only one game by the youngest Serbian GM ever.} 13. Nd2 Bb4 14. Qxb7 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 O-O 16. Be2 $1 (16. Qxe4 $6 Qa5+ $1 17. Kd1 Bb3+ $1 {Harshavardhan,G (2433)-Budisavljevic,L (2524) Cala Gonone ITA 2022} 18. axb3 Qxa1+ 19. Ke2 Qxb2+ 20. Kf3 Qxb3+ 21. Bd3 f5 22. Qe3 $11 {[%csl Rf3] The position is equal, but I prefer Black's pieces.}) 16... Qa5+ (16... Qxd4+ 17. Ke1 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1] /}) 17. b4 Qg5+ 18. Ke1 Qxg2 19. Rf1 Rc8 20. d5 Bg4 21. Bxg4 Qxg4 22. d6 $13 {The position is equal, but a few good moves are still required from Black to save the game.}) 13. Kd1 dxe4 14. Qxb7 O-O $1 (14... exf3 $4 15. Qxb4 Nc6 {Srihari,L (2302)-Gholami,A (2541) New Delhi IND 2020} 16. Qc5 $1 Nxd4 17. Ke1 $3 {What an amazing move to secure the win. There is no serious threat to our king.} Qd5 (17... Bg4 18. g3 Bf5 19. Rc1 $18) 18. Qxd5 Bxd5 19. g3 Nc2+ 20. Kd2 Nxa1 21. Bxa6 Nb3+ 22. axb3 Bxb3 23. Re1+ $18) 15. Qxe4 Bd5 16. Qd3 $13 {[%cal Ga2a3,Ga1c1,Gf1e2] The position remains tense, and both outcomes are possible.}) (9. Qc2 Bb4 $1 $11 {[%cal Gb4c3]}) 9... Qd8 (9... b5 $5 {Played twice by the very talented IM/WGM Garcia Martin. She aims to neutralize White's queenside activity and, at the right moment, transfer the rook to e7.} 10. a4 b4 11. a5 $1 c6 12. Na4 Bd6 13. e3 O-O 14. Bd3 Re7 {[%cal Ge6g4]} (14... Bg4 15. Ne5 $1 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 15. h3 $1 Qh6 16. Qc2 Kh8 17. Nc5 $5 (17. Rf1 {[%cal Re6g4]} f5 $1 18. O-O-O f4 19. Kb1 fxe3 20. fxe3 Bg8 $11 {Guichard,P (2409)-Garcia Martin,M (2324) Terme Catez SLO 2021}) 17... Bg4 $1 18. O-O-O Bxf3 19. gxf3 $13 {[%csl Ra6,Rb4,Rb8][%cal Gc1b1] White has a slightly more pleasant position, which the engine evaluates as "+0.15.}) 10. h4 {[%cal Gf3g5]} h6 {[%cal Rf3g5]} (10... Be7 11. Qc2 h6 12. e4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 c6 14. Bd3 Nd7 15. O-O-O Nf6 16. Qe3 Nd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Kb1 b5 19. Ne5 $13 {[%cal Gg2g4] With mutual chances.}) 11. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Nd7 (11... Bd6 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 {I think this could be an interesting alternative to previous games. We keep the queens on the board, prepare for a long castle, and plan to attack with g4 at the right moment.} (13. Qxe4 Qe7 $1 (13... Kf8 14. O-O-O Nd7 15. Ne5 $18 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gf2f4] Vidit,S (2726)-Gukesh,D (2578) chess24.com INT 2021}) (13... O-O 14. Bd3 $18 {[%cal Ge1c1,Ge4h7]}) (13... c6 14. d5 $1 cxd5 15. Qd4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd4a7,Gd4g7]}) 14. O-O-O {A critical position for Black. He should continue with} Bb3 $1 (14... c6 $2 15. Bd3 Nd7 16. Bc2 Nf6 17. Qd3 Ra8 18. Rhe1 Rd8 19. Kb1 $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ge8d7,Gd7c8,Gc2b3] /. Holm,K (2450)-Haldorsen,B (2477) Oslo NOR 2021}) 15. Re1 Qxe4 16. Rxe4+ Kd8 (16... Kf8 $6 17. Ne5 $1 $14) 17. Nd2 $1 Be6 18. Bc4 Bf5 19. Re3 $13 {[%csl Ra7,Rd8][%cal Gh1d1,Gg2g3,Gd2e4] White has slightly better chances and a more pleasant position.}) 13... O-O 14. O-O-O Nd7 15. Kb1 Re8 16. Ne5 Nf6 17. Bd3 c6 18. f4 $13 {[%cal Gg2g4] The position looks a little uncomfortable for Black. We plan to continue with a strong g4-g5 attack, but I'm not sure what the chances are of Black finding decent counterplay.}) 12. e4 dxe4 (12... c6 $2 {A big strategy mistake. After the powerful push} 13. e5 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] White secures a dominant pawn structure. I'm not worried about Black's potential counterplay with ...c5, because White's plan of Bf5, followed by Nf4 and g4, poses far greater threats. The pressure on Black's kingside becomes immense, and Black's pieces will struggle to find activity as White steadily builds up an overwhelming attack.} Be7 14. Bd3 b5 15. Ne2 $16 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gd3f5,Gg2g4] Krstulovic,A (2447)-Creanga,R (2182) Arad ROU 2023}) 13. Nxe4 Be7 (13... c6 14. Bc4 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 Be7 16. O-O-O O-O 17. g4 $40 {[%cal Gg4g5] g5 is coming, and the position looks extremely promising}) 14. O-O-O {[%cal Gf1c4,Gf3e5]} c6 15. Bc4 (15. Ne5 O-O 16. g4 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qa5 18. f4 b5 19. Ng5 Bxg5 20. hxg5 b4 21. gxh6 g6 22. a4 Bxg4 23. Rd6 $13 {Black is already under significant pressure and requires precise defense.}) 15... Bxc4 16. Qxc4 O-O 17. Qd3 Nf6 $2 (17... b5 $1 18. Kb1 $13 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] White has a promising position filled with attacking ideas, but Black remains solid for now. Although White's plans, such as pushing pawns and activating pieces, create potential threats, Black's defenses are still holding up. White will need to carefully coordinate his pieces to break through, while Black must find accurate counterplay in order to maintain his solidity.}) 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. g4 $1 g6 {Mosesov,D (2405)-Samunenkov,I (2369) Lviv UKR 2021} 20. Ne5 $1 Qd5 21. f4 $14 {[%cal Gg4g5]} *

