{[%evp 0,33,28,25,26,-2,-3,-11,13,17,16,16,2,-16,-16,-16,0,5,-4,-9,-5,-17,-10,-29,-13,-50,-44,-44,-46,-27,-37,-12,12,17,21,-25]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 $1 {Most principal move. We will directly transpose into the Nimzo-Indian 4.f3 line, but in a better version for White, since Black has already played ..d5.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Nf6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 O-O (7... Bf5 $5 {[%cal Rf1d3] Black would be happy to exchange bishops here, but we won't allow him to achieve that. Instead, we'll unleash a storm of pawns at him.} 8. f3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4]} O-O 9. Ne2 c5 (9... Re8 $2 {Bad move. It helps us achieve our goal with tempo.} 10. g4 Bxg4 $2 {I suppose this was the idea behind 9...Re8, but it doesn't work at all. After} (10... Bg6 11. h4 h5 12. g5 Nfd7 {Elissa (2449)-Intagrand (2574) playchess.com INT 2006} 13. Ng3 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gd1f3]}) 11. fxg4 Nxg4 {L'Ami,E (2605)-Karavade,E (2421) Douglas ENG 2016.. we can simply continue with} 12. Rg1 $1 {[%cal Rd8h4,Gg1g3] allowing us to reach a winning position with no compensation for Black.} Nxe3 13. Qd3 $1 Qh4+ 14. Rg3 Nxf1 15. Kxf1 Nd7 (15... Qxh2 16. Rh3 $18 {[%csl Rh2]}) 16. Rg2 $18 {[%cal Gc1g5]}) 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nf4 Nc6 12. Be2 Rc8 13. Ra2 cxd4 14. cxd4 h5 $1 15. h3 Bh7 16. O-O $13 {An interesting position for both sides. White has a slightly more pleasant position, thanks to the bishop pair and a space advantage.}) 8. Bd3 c5 (8... b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] Playing Ba6 with the idea of delaying ..c5 a little is also a fine continuation for Black.} 9. Ne2 Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qd3 $1 {Move order is imporant here: after 11.0-0, if Black replies with 11...c5 and White follows up with 12.Qd3, Black has the strong response 12...Nc7!} Qc8 $6 (11... Nb8 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 $5 {A new, interesting way of treating this position. We can always go for 13.f3, transposing to the main line, but it's definitely worth checking this non-typical way of playing this structure.} (13. f3 Re8 14. Ng3 Nc6 15. Bb2 h5 16. Rae1 {transpose to the main line.}) 13... Nbd7 $5 {This is the critical test. Nevertheless, we'll gladly accept the pawn sacrifice, and with a model game, I'll show you a best setup for White.} (13... bxc5 14. c4 dxc4 15. Qxc4 Nbd7 16. e4 Qe7 $1 (16... Qb6 17. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Ra8b8] A slightly more precise move than 17.f3, as it takes control of the b8-square, cutting off Rab8-Qb3 counterplay.} (17. f3 Rab8 18. Bf4 Qb3 19. Rfc1 Qxc4 20. Rxc4 Rb7 21. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4] Tabatabaei,M (2677)-Yuffa,D (2592) Sharjah UAE 2023}) 17... Rfe8 18. f3 Ne5 19. Bxe5 Rxe5 20. Rab1 $14 {[%csl Ya7,Yc5][%cal Gf1d1,Ge2c3] /}) 17. f3 Ne5 18. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Ya7,Yc5][%cal Gc1e3] We have a slightly better structure and a pleasant position to play for the win.}) 14. cxb6 axb6 15. Rb1 $1 {Rb4-a4, followed by Qb1 and Rd1. Even in the best-case scenario, Black can claim some compensation, but nothing more substantial.} Ne5 (15... Ra5 $5 {[%cal Ga5c5]} 16. Rb4 $1 {[%cal Gd3b1]} Qc7 17. Qb1 Re8 18. Rd1 h6 19. h3 Rc5 20. Bd2 Ra8 21. Nd4 Qe5 22. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd2e1,Ga3a4,Yc3c4] Sokolov,I (2646)-Arizmendi Martinez,J (2544) Linares 2014}) 16. Qc2 Nc4 17. a4 Ra5 18. Rd1 Qc7 19. Rb4 Rfa8 20. h3 h6 21. Nd4 Qd7 22. Nb5 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2e1] Sutormin,D (2393)-Ljepic,A (2356) Novi Sad SRB 2024}) 12. O-O c5 13. f3 Re8 14. Ng3 Qb7 15. Ra2 $14 {[%cal Ga2e2] We already know how to treat this position: Re2, preparing for the right moment to play e4!}) 9. Ne2 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} (9... Nc6 10. O-O Re8 11. f3 {With the same ideas as in the main lines, I propose transferring the rook to e2 via a2. Another plan could be Nf4-g4, followed by Ra2-Rg2, launching an attack!}) (9... c4 $2 {was played in more than 50 games. I think that 9...c4 is not the right moment to close the center, as at some point, it will be hard to fight against f3-e4.} 10. Bc2 Nc6 11. O-O Re8 12. f3 b5 13. Ng3 {[%cal Ge3e4]} h5 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gh4h3] As we will see in the main line, this is a typical way for Black to react against White's preparation for e4.} 14. h4 $3 $16 {I'm proud to show you this beautiful novelty. The h4-pawn is untouchable, while e4 is coming soon, and Black can't do anything to prevent it.} (14. e4 h4 15. Nh1 $1 (15. Nf5 $2 {Kucuksari,K (2369)-Vusatiuk,V (2323) chess.com INT 2021} Bxf5 16. exf5 a5 $15 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb5b4]}) 15... dxe4 16. fxe4 Nxe4 17. Qf3 Qd5 18. Bxe4 Rxe4 19. Nf2 Bf5 20. Bd2 Nxd4 21. cxd4 Rxd4 22. Qxd5 Rxd5 23. Ba5 Re8 24. Rae1 $16 {Geirnaert,S (2441)-Grochal,J (2184) Wachtebeke BEL 2016}) 14... Qc7 (14... a5 15. e4 $1 dxe4 16. fxe4 Ng4 17. Bg5 $1 f6 18. Bc1 $1 $18 {[%cal Rd8h4,Gg3h5]}) 15. Qe1 Na5 16. e4 $1 {Once we achieve e4 without any counterplay from Black, the game is essentially decided. We will have a strategically winning position.} Nb3 17. Rb1 Nxc1 18. Rxc1 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gf3f4]} Qf4 {is Black's only hope to prevent 19.e5 followed by 20.f4.} 19. e5 Qxh4 20. Rb1 Rb8 21. Ne2 Qxe1 22. Rfxe1 Nh7 23. Nf4 $16 {[%csl Rd5,Rh5][%cal Gf4h5,Gf4d5]}) 10. O-O Ba6 11. f3 Re8 (11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nc6 $2 (12... Re8 13. Ng3 Nc6 14. Bb2 h5 {transpose to the main line.}) 13. e4 $1 cxd4 (13... Qd7 14. Bg5 $1 c4 15. Qc2 Ne8 {Ibragimov,I (2584)-Kacheishvili,G (2584) Connecticut 2002} 16. a4 $16 {[%cal Rb6b5,Ge2g3] Ng3 won’t escape. First, we stop Black's counterplay with ...b5}) 14. cxd4 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5] e5 is coming. White has a dominant position.}) 12. Ng3 Bxd3 (12... Qc8 $6 {The idea behind this move is that after the pawn exchange on e4, Black's Qc3 hits both the rook on a1 and the d4 pawn.} 13. e4 $1 cxd4 14. cxd4 dxe4 15. fxe4 $18 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] We've achieved our goal!} Qc3 {[%cal Gc3a1,Gc3d4]} (15... Qg4 $5 16. Qxg4 Nxg4 17. Bxa6 Nxa6 18. e5 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh2h3] Beautiful move! We restrict the knight on g4. The threat is 19.h3, forcing 19...Nh6, and after 20.Bxh6, we damage Black's kingside pawn structure.} Nc7 19. h3 Nh6 20. Bxh6 gxh6 {[%csl Rf7,Rh6,Rh7] Georgiev,V (2553)-Ginsburg,M (2367) Los Angeles 2011} 21. Rf3 Rad8 22. Nf5 $18 {[%cal Ga1f1,Gf3g3,Gg3g7]}) 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 (16... Qxa1 17. Bb7 $18 {[%csl Ra8]}) 17. Ra2 $1 Rad8 {Esipenko,A (2682)-Gharibyan,M (2433) lichess.org INT 2020. Here's a critical moment for us. We need to continue with the brave} 18. Nf5 $1 $146 Nc5 (18... Rxe4 19. Rc2 Qa5 20. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5d8]} Re6 21. Qf3 $18 {[%cal Gg5h6,Gf5g7,Gf3g3]}) (18... Nxe4 19. Rc2 $1 Qb3 20. Qg4 g6 21. Nh6+ $18 {[%cal Gh6f7,Gf1f7]}) 19. e5 $1 {Final touch. After this move, Black's position falls apart.} Nfe4 (19... Rxe5 20. Bd2 $1 Qb3 21. Qxb3 Nxb3 22. dxe5 $18) 20. Qg4 g6 21. dxc5 $18) (12... Qd7 $6 {[%cal Gd7b7,Yb8a6,Ya6c7,Yd7b5] An interesting place for the queen. She can be repositioned to b7, where Black can either offer a queen trade with ..Qa6 or reinforce the queenside pawn advance with ..c5 and ..b5.} 13. e4 $1 $146 {Beautiful novelty! We're not waiting for Black to regroup, and we're using this to achieve our main goal.} cxd4 (13... Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Kh8 15. e5 Ng8 16. f4 $18 {[%cal Gf4f5,Yg3f5]}) 14. Bg5 $1 {An energetic continuation! We take advantage of the queen not being on d8. Now, e5 becoming a powerful threat.} dxc3 (14... Re6 15. e5 $3 Ne8 16. cxd4 $18 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf3f4]}) 15. e5 $3 c2 (15... Rxe5 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. f4 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 $18 {[%cal Gg3h5,Gd3g3]}) 16. Bxc2 Bxf1 17. exf6 Bc4 18. fxg7 $18 {[%cal Gg3f5]}) (12... h5 $2 {Too early for Black's key idea. We simply claim a big advantage after} 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. e4 $1 $18 {[%cal Ge4e5]} h4 15. Nf5 dxe4 16. fxe4 $40 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gd1g4,Gd1f3]}) 13. Qxd3 Nc6 14. Bb2 {Critical moment. In practice, Black has tried over five different ideas here, and we'll examine each one. In my opinion, the only way is to play immidiately} h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gh4h3] Key idea for Black!} (14... c4 $6 {Together with 14...h5, one of Black's top choices. Black will still continue with the key idea of ...h5-h4, but in this position, it will be easier for him to create counterplay on the queenside with a5-b5-b4.} 15. Qd2 h5 16. Qf2 $1 h4 $1 (16... Qd7 {[%cal Rd7f5,Rg3f5] The most played move in the database, but not the most precise. After this move, we claim an advantage after} 17. Rae1 $1 Ne7 {As we'll see in the main line, the standard defensive maneuver for Black is usually Ne7-Ng6.} (17... Re6 $2 {Definitely the wrong way to fight against the e4 push.} 18. e4 $1 $18 g6 {[%cal Rg3f5]} (18... h4 19. Nf5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf3,Gf5]} h3 (19... Nh7 20. e5 $18 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5,Rh4][%cal Gf5h4]}) 20. Qg3 {[%csl Gf5,Gg3,Rg7]} g6 21. e5 $18 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf3f4]}) (18... Ne7 19. e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]} h4 20. Ne2 Ne8 21. Qxh4 $18 {Black has lost a pawn, and very soon he will lose the game.}) (18... dxe4 19. fxe4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} h4 20. Nf5 Nxe4 {Black repeatedly overextends in an attempt to win that pawn, but in the process, they become vulnerable to a strong kingside attack} 21. Qf4 $1 Nf6 22. Nxg7 Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Nd5 24. Qh6 f6 25. Nh5 $18 {Peralta,F (2568)-Edouard,R (2527) Barcelona ESP 2024}) 19. e5 Ne8 20. Ne2 $1 $18 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gg2g4]} (20. Bc1 f6 21. exf6 Nxf6 22. Rxe6 Qxe6 23. Re1 Qf7 24. Bg5 $16 {Bok,B (2620)-Ris,R (2410) Netherlands NED 2018})) (17... h4 $6 18. Nh1 $1 {[%csl Rh4] I'll be back!} h3 19. Ng3 $1 {And here we are, back in the battle! e4 is coming!} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6]} (19... b5 20. e4 a5 21. e5 Nh7 22. f4 f5 23. Qc2 Rf8 24. gxh3 $14 {[%cal Gh3h4,Gg1h1,Gh4h5,Gf1g1,Gb2c1] /. In the next few moves, we will prepare an attack on the g-file!}) 20. e4 $1 Ng6 21. Bc1 Nh4 22. gxh3 Qxh3 23. e5 $1 (23. Bg5 Nh7 24. Bxh4 $18 {Grozdanovic,A (2045)-Djordjevic,V (2360) Nis SRB 2024}) 23... Nh7 24. Ne2 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg1h1,Gf2g3,Ge2f4]} Nf5 (24... Rad8 {[%csl Gd5]} 25. Qg3 Qxg3+ 26. hxg3 Ng6 27. f4 $18 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf4,Gg3][%cal Gf4f5,Gg3g4]}) 25. Nf4 Qh4 26. Nxd5 $18) 18. e4 h4 19. Nh1 $1 (19. Ne2 $2 dxe4 20. fxe4 Ng6 21. e5 Ng4 $132 {[%cal Gg4e5]}) 19... dxe4 (19... h3 20. e5 $1 hxg2 21. Qxg2 Nh7 22. Ng3 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4,Re7f5,Rg2h3]}) 20. fxe4 Ng6 21. e5 Nd5 (21... Ng4 22. Qf3 $18 {[%cal Rg4e5] Now the idea behind 19.Nh1 becomes clear. Unlike in the 19.Ne2 line, there will be no sacrifice on e5.}) 22. Qf3 $13 {[%cal Gh1f2,Gf2h3,Gh3g5,Gf3h5,Gb2c1,Ge1e4] An interesting position has arisen, but I wouldn't play this from Black's perspective without any counterplay on the queenside. White has many attacking ideas, starting with Nf2, followed by Nh3 and Qh5, or potentially Ng5. Additionally, White can bring pieces into the attack, such as Bc1 or Re4}) 17. Nf5 Qd7 $1 $146 (17... h3 {Liu,Z (2133)-Li Ruofan (2351) Hanoi VIE 2018} 18. Qg3 $1 g6 19. e4 $16 {[%cal Gf5h6,Gg3h3,Gb2c1]}) 18. Nxh4 (18. e4 dxe4 19. fxe4 Rxe4 20. Nxg7 Ng4 21. Qf5 Qxf5 22. Nxf5 Ne7 $11) 18... b5 19. Rab1 a5 $1 (19... Na5 20. g4 $16) 20. Bc1 g6 21. Qg3 b4 22. axb4 axb4 23. cxb4 Ra2 24. Qf4 Nh5 25. Qg5 $13 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gb5b6,Ye3e4] With mutual chances.}) (14... Rc8 $2 {The idea behind this move is that after pushing e4 and trading all the pawns in the center, Black can follow up with Ne5 and Nc4.} 15. e4 $1 {It's the third choice in the database, but the strongest one! We don't need to prepare e4; we can push it immediately!} (15. Rae1 $1) 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 dxe4 17. fxe4 Ne5 {[%cal Rd8d3]} 18. Qe2 Nc4 19. Rae1 $1 Nxb2 (19... Qd7 $2 {This move appears in every line so far, including the main line. It's crucial to note that it often opens up the possibility for a rook sacrifice on f6.} 20. Rxf6 $3 gxf6 21. Nh5 Re6 22. Qg4+ Kf8 23. Bc3 Ke7 24. d5 Ne5 25. Qg3 Rxc3 26. Qxc3 $18 {[%cal Gh5f6,Yh5g3,Yg3f5] Stinka,J (2309)-Bernasek,J (2515) Czech Republic CZE 2023}) (19... b5 $6 {makes no sense since it allows us to keep an important bishop that will play a huge part in the attack on the Black king.} 20. Ba1 $1 Rc6 {Megalios,K (2382)-Rasulov,V (2516) Vrnjacka Banja SRB 2023} (20... Qb6 21. Kh1 Rc7 22. d5 Nd7 23. Nf5 {[%csl Ga1,Gd5,Ge4,Gf5]} Nde5 24. Bd4 $18 {Pulse_exchange,R (2414)-Ciron (2537) playchess.com 2007}) 21. d5 $1 Ra6 22. Nf5 $18 {[%csl Ga1,Gf5][%cal Ge2f2,Gf2g3,Rf5g7]}) 20. Qxb2 Ng4 {[%cal Gd8h4]} 21. h3 Nh6 22. e5 $1 {[%csl Rh6]} Rc4 (22... Qd5 $5 {[%csl Gd5] aiming to block the pawn, double rooks on the c-file, and seek counterplay, doesn't stop us from playing} 23. Qf2 $1 {where we can simply continue our attack.} Rc4 24. Rd1 Rec8 25. Nh5 $18 {[%cal Gf2g3]}) 23. Rf4 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Gf4]} f6 24. Qb3 Qd5 25. Nh5 $1 $18 {We have a completely winning position. I'll leave the rest of the game so you can see the beautiful finish by Anton!} Kh8 26. Kh2 fxe5 27. Rxe5 Rxe5 28. dxe5 Rc5 29. Qxd5 Rxd5 30. Rf8+ Ng8 31. Nf6 gxf6 32. exf6 Rg5 33. g4 Rg6 34. f7 Rg7 35. g5 {1-0 Anton Guijarro,D (2642)-Abdusattorov,N (2560) Moscow RUS 2019.}) (14... Na5 $6 {A very similar idea to 14...Rc8. Black wants to occupy the c4 square and create counterplay on the c-file.} 15. e4 $1 Nc4 16. Bc1 $1 {Once again, we keep the bishop for our future attack.} cxd4 17. cxd4 b5 (17... Kh8 18. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5d8]} h6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. f4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gf4f5,Ge4e5]}) 18. e5 Nd7 19. f4 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gg1h1] Kovacevic,B (2493)-Kovacevic,V (2512) Solin 2005. We succeeded in our goal. We have a strong center and a dominant position.}) (14... Qd7 $6 {[%csl Rf6] wouldn't stop us from playing} 15. e4 $1 Rf8 (15... dxe4 16. fxe4 Qg4 {With the idea of putting pressure on the center, but after} 17. Rae1 $1 Rad8 18. h3 Qg6 19. Re3 $18 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gg3f5] we maintain a strong center and Nf5 is coming.}) 16. Rae1 c4 17. Qc2 (17. Qd2 $1) 17... b5 18. e5 Ne8 19. f4 $18 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf4] Ushenina,A (2458)-Daulyte,D (2419) Kigali TUR 2017}) 15. Rae1 h4 (15... g6 $6 {[%cal Rg3f5] prevents us from jumping to f5, but that's not a problem since we can reroute the knight via Nh1-f2 to h3 or g4, depending on the position.} 16. e4 h4 17. Nh1 Nh5 {Blohberger,F (2488)-Roseneck,J (2402) Austria AUT 2022} 18. Nf2 $1 {Beautiful improvement over previous games!} Nf4 19. Qb5 Rc8 20. Bc1 Nh5 (20... g5 21. Ng4 Kg7 22. g3 Ng6 23. f4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gf4f5]} (23. Qb2 $18 {[%cal Gb2f2,Ge4e5,Gf3f4]})) 21. dxc5 bxc5 22. Rd1 $18 {[%csl Rd5]}) (15... Qd7 $5 {Just like 14...Qd7, it doesn't prevent us from playing} 16. e4 $1 h4 17. Nf5 h3 18. e5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]} hxg2 19. Kxg2 Nh5 {Yordanov,L (2311)-Metodiev,V (2030) Primorsko BUL 2020} 20. f4 $18 {[%cal Gb2c1,Gd3h3]}) (15... cxd4 16. cxd4 h4 17. Nf5 h3 (17... Nh5 {A reaction from many players. The idea is to occupy the f4 square and bring the queen to g5, creating some attacking chances.} 18. e4 Qf6 {Botvinnik,M-Kurajica,B Hastings 1966} (18... g6 {Usually a bad reaction from Black. Leaving the king open helps us nearly win the game by force.} 19. Nh6+ Kg7 20. Ng4 Nf6 {Schneider,A (2360)-Tolnai,T (2470) Hungary 1995} 21. e5 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]} Nh7 22. Qd2 Qg5 23. Ne3 $18 {[%cal Gf3f4]}) 19. f4 $1 {[%cal Rh5f4,Ge4e5]} dxe4 20. Rxe4 Rad8 21. d5 Qxb2 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. dxc6 $16 {[%cal Gc6c7,Gd3d7]}) 18. e4 (18. g4 {A solid alternative to 18.e4.} Ne7 $1 {As we’ll see in the main line, this is usually Black's best defense. The knight moves to g6, where it defends the king and also contributes to counterplay against our king.} 19. Ng3 Qd7 {Wei Yi (2722)-Maghsoodloo,P (2720) chess.com INT 2022} 20. e4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5]} dxe4 21. fxe4 Qxg4 22. d5 $36 {[%cal Gd5d6,Gg1h1,Gg3f5]}) 18... hxg2 19. Rf2 Nh5 (19... Ne7 $1 20. Ng3 Ng6 $13) 20. f4 $5 {Taking the critical f4 square from Black, while preparing e5 or f5 depending on Black's response.} dxe4 $2 (20... g6 $1 {It was the only way to save the position, but it's very difficult to find over the board.} 21. e5 (21. Qh3 Qc8 22. Qxg2 Rxe4 23. Nh6+ Kg7 24. Rxe4 dxe4 25. Qg5 f6 26. d5 Ne5 $1 27. Bxe5 e3 $3 $11) 21... gxf5 22. Rxg2+ Kf8 23. Qh3 Nxf4 24. Qh6+ Ke7 25. Qxf4 Rg8 26. Rg5 Kd7 {was the only defense for Black!}) 21. Qh3 g6 22. Rxg2 Kf8 23. Ne3 Nxd4 24. Bxd4 Qxd4 25. f5 $18 {Dai,C (2536)-Yu Shaoteng (2482) Qiziwan CHN 2023. This game represents the classic example of what can happen after we take the crucial f4 square from Black.}) 16. Nf5 h3 $1 (16... Nh5 {[%cal Yh5f4,Gd8f6,Gf6g5]} 17. e4 $1 $14 Qf6 {The most logical response from Black, as it temporarily prevents the e5 push and is useful both in defense and for potential counterplay with ...Nf4-Qg6.} (17... cxd4 $2 18. cxd4 Qf6 19. f4 $1 $16 {transpose to 15...cxd4.}) (17... g6 $2 {As we already saw in the previous lines, ...g6 is usually a poor response from Black. Leaving the king exposed helps us nearly win the game by force.} 18. Nh6+ Kg7 19. Ng4 Qg5 (19... Rc8 {Devaev,A (2325)-Javakhadze,Z (2417) chess.com 2024} 20. c4 $1 $18 {[%csl Gb2,Rg7]}) 20. c4 {[%csl Gb2,Rg7]} dxe4 21. dxc5+ Kh7 22. Qd5 Qxd5 23. cxd5 $18 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5] Bashylina,L (2124)-Bashirov,K (2328) Budapest HUN 2024}) (17... Re6 $6 {Gholami Orimi,M (2470)-Aditya,V (2326) Dubai UAE 2024} 18. Bc1 $1 $18 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Ge4e5]}) ({It's kind of late for} 17... c4 {since we've already managed to play e4, from where we'll continue with our plan on the kingside.} 18. Qd2 Qf6 (18... g6 $2 {Always a poor response..} 19. Nh6+ Kg7 20. Ng4 Rh8 {Zamar Kodelja,J (2190)-Mesaros,F (2416) Montevideo URU 2017} 21. Bc1 b5 22. Qf2 a5 23. f4 $18 {[%cal Gf4f5]}) 19. Bc1 Ne7 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Qf2 b5 22. g4 hxg3 23. hxg3 $18 {[%cal Gg3g4,Ge4e5,Gg1g2,Gf1h1]}) (17... h3 $6 {The key idea for Black in the main line fails with ...Nh5, as it allows us to strengthen the center and seize control of the f4 square.} 18. g3 $1 Ne7 19. e5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]} Qd7 20. Nd6 Rf8 21. Nxf7 $18 {Matlakov,M (2692)-Bellahcene,B (2560) Dubai UAE 2019}) 18. Bc1 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] Securing the important f4 square.} (18. e5 Nf4 $132 {[%cal Gf6g6]}) 18... Ne7 (18... cxd4 $6 19. exd5 $1 {Important intermezzo!} Ne7 20. Rxe7 Rxe7 21. Nxe7+ Qxe7 22. Qxd4 $16 {[%csl Gc1,Gd5,Rh5][%cal Gf1d1,Gd5d6]}) 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 (19... Rxe7 $2 {would be a terrible blunder since it allows us to win the game in a beautiful way!} 20. e5 Qg6 21. Qxg6 fxg6 22. Bg5 {[%csl Re7,Rh4]} Rc7 23. c4 $3 dxc4 24. d5 $18 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5]}) 20. e5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]} cxd4 21. cxd4 g6 22. Bd2 Ng7 23. f4 Qe6 (23... Nf5 24. g4 hxg3 25. hxg3 $18 {[%cal Gg3g4]}) 24. f5 {A fine sacrifice of a pawn!} Nxf5 25. Rf4 $13 {[%cal Ge1f1] Black is already under significant pressure, and White has a promising position.}) 17. Ng3 (17. e4 $5 {Played in only a few games, I believe this move presents one of the few dangerous challenges for Black.} hxg2 (17... Ne7 {Ne7-g6 should be the standard defense for Black, which unfortunately is not used as much as it should be.} 18. Ng3 Ng6 (18... hxg2 19. Kxg2 Ng6 20. Kh1 Nf4 21. Qe3 N6h5 22. Rg1 $40 {[%cal Gg3h5,Gg1g5]}) 19. Bc1 $13 {[%cal Gc1g5]}) 18. Rf2 Nh5 (18... Ne7 19. Ng3 Ng6 20. Bc1 dxe4 21. fxe4 Ng4 22. Rf5 cxd4 23. cxd4 $13 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gd3d1]}) (18... cxd4 $6 19. Rxg2 $1 Nh5 20. Bc1 $16 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gg5h6]}) 19. f4 $1 {Taking the critical f4 square from Black, while preparing e5 or f5 depending on Black's response.} (19. Rxg2 Ne7 $1 (19... g6 {Ebrahimi Herab,H (2386)-Kucza,K (2346) chess.com INT 2024} 20. Bc1 $18 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) 20. Nh6+ (20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Bc1 dxe4 22. fxe4 Qh4 23. Qe2 Nf4 24. Bxf4 Qxf4 25. Rg4 Qh6 26. Rf1 cxd4 27. cxd4 Rac8 $132) 20... Kf8 21. e5 $13 {[%cal Rg7h6,Rb2c1,Ye7g6,Yh6f7] Even though this position looks quite dangerous for Black, I prefer 19.f4 as it brings more dynamism and complications, where Black can easily make a mistake.}) 19... Ne7 $1 (19... g6 $5 20. e5 $3 cxd4 (20... gxf5 21. Rxg2+ Kf8 22. Qh3 Nxf4 23. Qh6+ Ke7 24. Qxf4 Rg8 25. Ree2 $16 Qc8 26. Qh4+ Kd7 27. Qf6 $16) 21. Qf3 Qd7 22. Nd6 Qxd6 23. exd6 Rxe1+ 24. Kxg2 Re4 25. Bc1 f5 26. Re2 Rd8 27. c4 Rde8 28. Rc2 $13 {With a few more precise moves, Black should be fine.}) (19... dxe4 $2 20. Qh3 $1 g6 21. Rxg2 {[%cal Gh3h5]} Kf8 22. Ne3 $1 $18 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gf4f5]}) 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Qh3 g6 22. f5 $40 {[%cal Gb2c1] Seeking an aggressive intrusion into Black's camp. With a few more precise defensive moves, Black has a chance to maintain a clear equality.}) (17. g4 $5 {Second most played move in the database, but after} Ne7 $1 {I don't see any dangerous threats from White.} 18. Ng3 Qd7 (18... Ng6 19. e4 Nf4 20. Qd2 Ng2 21. Re2 dxe4 22. fxe4 Nxg4 23. Nf5 $13) 19. dxc5 bxc5 20. c4 Qc6 21. g5 Nd7 22. Nh5 Qg6 23. Qxg6 fxg6 24. Nxg7 Reb8 25. Re2 dxc4 $11) 17... hxg2 (17... Ne7 18. e4 Ng6 19. Bc1 {transposes to 17.e4, which has already been analyzed.}) (17... Nh7 $6 18. e4 dxe4 (18... c4 19. Qc2 b5 20. e5 a5 21. f4 $18 {Pranav,A (2340)-Tukhaev,A (2527) Taleigao IND 2019}) 19. fxe4 hxg2 20. Rf2 $1 $16) (17... Qd7 {The idea behind this is that after ...hxg2, Black prevents Rf2 with ...Qh3, forcing White to capture the pawn on g2 with the king.} 18. e4 hxg2 19. Kxg2 dxe4 20. fxe4 Ne5 21. Qe2 $5 (21. Qd1 Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gg6h4,Gd7h3] Important improvement over the previous game.} (21... cxd4 $2 22. cxd4 Qb5 23. Bc3 Ng6 24. d5 Rac8 25. Bxf6 gxf6 26. Nf5 $18 {Kiolbasa,O (2351)-Socko,M (2419) Walbrzych POL 2024}) 22. e5 Nh4+ 23. Kg1 Qh3 24. Qe2 Rad8 25. Qf2 Ng4 26. Qxf7+ Kh7 27. Qh5+ Kg8 $11) 21... Ng6 22. Rxf6 $5 {Why not!? This is likely the most challenging and daunting move. It demands precise play from Black to maintain equality.} (22. Kh1 {Could be a solid alternative.}) 22... gxf6 23. Rf1 {[%cal Gg2h1,Gg3h5,Yd4d5]} cxd4 (23... Nh4+ 24. Kh1 Qh3 25. Nh5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rf6]}) 24. cxd4 Rac8 $1 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gc8c6,Gg3h5]} 25. Kh1 Qh3 (25... Kf8 26. a4 {[%cal Gb2a3]} Qh3 (26... Qxa4 $2 27. Qf3 $18 {[%cal Gd4d5]}) 27. d5 $36) 26. d5 $36 {[%cal Ge2f2,Gf1g1] The position is level, but still requires some precision in defense.}) 18. Kxg2 $1 cxd4 {Played in both games in the database.} (18... Ne7 19. e4 Ng6 20. Kh1 Nf4 21. Qe3 N6h5 22. Rg1 cxd4 23. cxd4 g6 24. Nxh5 Nxh5 25. Rg5 Ng7 26. Reg1 $14) (18... Qd7 19. e4 dxe4 20. fxe4 Ne5 21. Qe2 Ng6 22. Rxf6 $5 {transposes to 17...Qd7.}) 19. cxd4 Ne7 20. e4 Ng6 21. Kh1 $5 (21. Bc1 dxe4 22. fxe4 Qd7 23. Kh1 $13 {[%cal Gc1g5]}) 21... Nf4 22. Qe3 N6h5 23. Rg1 $40 {[%cal Gg3h5,Gg1g5] . The position demonstrates our aggressive intentions with this line. The conclusion is that Black must respond with the key idea of a quick h5-h4. Any other 'popular' responses would allow us to push e4, gaining a dominant position. After 18.Kg2!, there are only a few games in the database, and I believe we can create significant problems for Black, even with his best defense.} *

