{[%evp 0,6,13,11,11,-6,-6,-6,4]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 dxc4 (3... f5 $2 {I was surprised to see that a few strong GMs played this move. Black aims for a Stonewall structure, but in a version that is much more favorable for us than usual.} 4. Nf3 (4. Nh3 $5 Nf6 5. Bg5 c6 6. Nf4 Be7 (6... Bd6 7. Nh5 $16) 7. e3 O-O 8. h4 $14) 4... Nf6 (4... c6 {In the Stonewall structure, what I love about this position is that we don't have e3, so we don’t need to go for the usual plan of playing b3, Bb2, Qc1, and Ba3 to trade off the dark-squared bishops in order to gain control over the dark squares. Controlling e5 is particularly important for us. That's why here, we play the natural Bf4, and it doesn't matter how aggressively Black starts attacking - we control the crucial e5 square. In the following lines, I'll show you how easy it is to handle such a position.} 5. Bf4 Nf6 (5... dxc4 $6 {Usually, it's not good to separate a structure like this.} 6. e3 b5 7. g4 $1 $16) 6. e3 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Ne4 9. h3 Nd7 10. Rc1 $1 {The following lines will demonstrate that Black can't prevent us from playing Ne5, followed by f3, driving the knight away from e4.} g5 (10... Kh8 {Preparing ...g5.} 11. Ne2 a5 12. Qc2 g5 13. Bh2 Bd6 14. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gf3f4]} Nxe5 (14... Bb8 15. f4 Nxe5 16. fxe5 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4]}) (14... Qf6 15. f3 $18) 15. Bxe5+ Nf6 (15... Bxe5 $2 16. dxe5 Nc5 17. cxd5 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 exd5 19. f4 $18 {[%csl Rc8,Ge2,Ge5] A closed position with a passed pawn on e5. The knight will dominate the bishop.}) 16. cxd5 Bxe5 (16... exd5 17. f4 $18 {[%csl Ge5]}) 17. dxe5 Nxd5 18. Bc4 $16 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gf2f4] An unpleasant e4 is coming. Once we eliminate the doubled pawns, Black's structure will be so weakened that he won’t have any plans for attacking us.}) 11. Bh2 Qe8 12. Ne2 h5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 $18 {Browne,W (2560)-Frenkel,F (2205) Concord 1995}) 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Ne4 {This is simply inevitable. Yes, Black has a strong outpost on e4, but trading the dark-squared bishops is crucial for us. It will make it much easier to fight for the e5 square.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Rc1 $1 Nd7 11. Ne2 a5 12. h3 Nd6 13. Qc2 Nf6 14. Ne5 Bd7 15. c5 Nf7 16. f3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Ge5,Gf3] This is the result of our strategy. We control the e5 square, and after 16.f3, we also control the e4 square. We will gradually build up our position, and it's important to note that Black can't capture on e5, as we would gain a strong outpost on d4.} Be8 17. Rf2 g5 18. Qc3 a4 19. g3 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gd1f1,Yg3g4] SlowChess Blitz 2.9 avx2 (3418)-Igel 3.5.5 (3502) tcec-chess.com INT 2023}) 4. e4 c5 (4... Nf6 $6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. Nf3 (6. d5 $5 {is a good alternative for us.} exd5 7. exd5 {[%csl Gd5]} a6 $1 (7... Bd6 $2 {is just a bad blunder. It's crucial for Black to secure the b5 square before making such a move.} 8. Qe2+ $1 Kf8 (8... Qe7 9. Nb5 $1 {Now we see the consequences of not controlling the b5 square.} Kf8 (9... O-O 10. Qxe7 Bxe7 11. Nc7 $18 {[%csl Ra8] Volkov,S (2622)-Milov,V (2645) playchess.com 2005}) 10. Nf3 Nbd7 11. Nxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O $18 {[%csl Rf8,Rh8]}) 9. h3 a6 10. a4 Bf5 11. Nf3 h6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 $16 {Kuljasevic,D (2501)-Sermek,D (2509) Sibenik 2008}) 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Qe2+ Qe7 10. O-O $1 Qxe2 11. Bxe2 {[%cal Gf3d2]} O-O (11... Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 O-O 14. a4 Nbd7 15. a5 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gd5,Gf3] Cuenca Jimenez,J (2558)-Cifuentes Parada,R (2426) Alicante ESP 2022.}) 12. Nd2 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4,Ga2a4] It looks like a good Benoni for us. With no queens on the board, there's no attack from Black. We have the bishop pair and a passed d-pawn, which is enough to secure a slightly better position for us.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 (7... Nc6 $6 {Horvath,J (2551)-Roschina,T (2293) Basel 2001} 8. Nxc6 $1 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 bxc6 10. f3 $16 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Ge4,Gf3,Gg2,Gh2][%cal Gc1e3,Gd1e2] Bad move, allowing us to transpose into an endgame with a badly damaged queenside structure.}) 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 {We have more active pieces and a better center.} Qe7 (10... a6 $2 {Shimanov,A (2639)-Aghayev,N (2368) Nakhchivan 2013} 11. Rfd1 $1 Qe7 (11... Qc7 12. Rac1 Qb8 13. Bb3 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8]}) 12. Bb3 Re8 13. Nf3 $16) (10... Ne5 11. Nc6 Qd6 (11... Nxc6 12. Bxc5 Re8 13. Nb5 $18 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gb5d6]}) 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Rac1 Rd8 15. e5 {It's important to remember that with a structure like this - e5 pawn vs e6-f7-g7-h7 - we always have strong attacking chances. Since it's crucial to continue aggressively, I propose the following line:} Ne8 {[%csl Ge5,Ye6,Yf7,Yg7,Yh7]} 16. Bd3 $1 g6 {[%csl Ye7,Yf6,Yg7,Yh6]} 17. h4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gh4h5] h5 is coming, and it's difficult for Black to complete development. There's always the threat of Ne4-Nf6 in the air.}) 11. Bb3 {[%cal Gf2f4]} Ne5 12. Na4 Nfg4 13. Nxc5 Nxe3 14. Rfc1 N3g4 15. h3 Nf6 16. Qe3 $14 {[%cal Ge3g3,Ge4e5,Yc1c3,Ya1c1] We have more active pieces, and Qg3-e5 poses a serious threat.}) 5. d5 $1 {It's important to note that this position can also arise from the Accepted Queen's Gambit after: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 3.e4 c5!? 4.d5 e6 5.Nc3. So, for anyone who plays 3.e4 in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, these lines will also be valuable.} exd5 (5... Nf6 $6 6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 $1 a6 $1 (7... Bd6 $2 8. Qe2+ $1 Kf8 (8... Qe7 $2 9. Nb5 $18) 9. Nf3 a6 10. a4 Bg4 11. h3 $1 Bh5 12. O-O (12. g4 $1 Bg6 13. g5 Nh5 14. O-O $16 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gf3h4]}) 12... Nbd7 {Saldano Dayer,H (2275)-Piscicelli,D (2340) Buenos Aires 1994} 13. g4 Bg6 14. Re1 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf3h4,Gc1d2]}) 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Qe2+ $1 {Transposes to 4...Nf6; 6.d5!?, where the position has already been analyzed.}) 6. Qxd5 $1 (6. exd5 Bd6 7. Bxc4 Ne7 $1 {Played only a few times, but it seems like the best move to maintain equality. Not only does Black avoid the unpleasant Qe2+, but the knight on g6 can also be much more useful than on f6.} (7... a6 8. Nf3 $1 ({Every single player went for the automatic} 8. a4 {which doesn't offer any advantage to White.} Nf6 9. Qe2+ Qe7 $11 {[%cal Rc3b5]}) 8... Nf6 9. Qe2+ $1 Qe7 10. O-O $14 {transposes to 5...Nf6; 7...a6!}) (7... Nf6 $2 8. Qe2+ $1 $16 {transposes to 5...Nf6; 7...Bd6?}) 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Nd7 10. b3 Nb6 11. Re1 Nxc4 12. bxc4 Ng6 (12... Bg4 $2 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Ng6 15. Rb1 b6 16. Nb5 Be5 17. Bb2 Bxb2 18. Rxb2 Re8 19. Rbe2 Rxe2 20. Qxe2 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Ge1,Ge2]}) 13. Qd3 Bd7 14. Bb2 $13 {White gets a nice, solid position, but I believe Black is still okay. While White has a solid setup, Black's position is also flexible, and there are no immediate threats, allowing Black to hold the balance and look for counterplay.}) 6... Qxd5 7. exd5 $1 (7. Nxd5 Bd6 8. Bxc4 Nf6 $1 {A very important move to maintain equality. It demonstrates why GM Dizdarevic is a great expert in this line.} 9. Nxf6+ gxf6 10. Ne2 Be6 11. Bb5+ Ke7 12. Nc3 a6 13. Bd3 $13 {Agdestein,S (2630)-Dizdarevic,E (2522) Tromso 2014}) 7... Bf5 $1 (7... a6 $2 8. Bf4 $1 Bf5 (8... b5 9. g3 $1 $16 {[%cal Gf1g2,Ge1c1]}) 9. O-O-O Nd7 {Matlakov,M (2651)-Timofeev,A (2547) Barnaul RUS 2024} 10. Nf3 O-O-O (10... b5 11. a4 Be7 (11... b4 12. Nb1 $16 {[%cal Gd5d6,Gf1c4]}) 12. Re1 Kf8) 11. Bxc4 Nb6 12. Bb3 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Rxd6 14. a4 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gh1e1,Ya4a5] A very pleasant position for White. We will kick the knight from b6 with a5, after which Nd2-Nc4 follows. The passed pawn and control of the e-file give us an even bigger advantage, and I don't see any counterplay for Black.}) (7... Nf6 8. Nf3 $1 a6 9. Bf4 b5 10. O-O-O {[%csl Gd5]} Be7 (10... Nh5 11. Bc7 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd5d6]}) 11. g3 $1 (11. Re1 $1 {looks good as well.} Kf8 12. g3 $14 {[%cal Gd5d6,Gf1g2]}) 11... O-O 12. Bg2 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gh1e1,Gf3d2,Gd2e4] /. The passed pawn is our main strength, and we should focus on it. For just one pawn, we gain much better development, while Black's pieces are really stuck with no solution to the threat of d6 at some point. The dragon from g2 will then become very valuable for us.}) 8. Bf4 Nd7 9. O-O-O O-O-O {It’s a crazy move, but it works! Otherwise, a painful fate would await.} (9... a6 $2 {It seems like the most logical move. Unfortunately for Black, after} 10. Bxc4 O-O-O (10... b5 $2 11. Be2 c4 12. g4 $1 (12. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf3d4,Gh1e1]}) 12... Bg6 13. Bc7 $16 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gd5d6,Gg1h3] Black looks paralyzed.}) 11. d6 $1 $16 {[%cal Gg1e2,Ge2g3] The position looks very bad for Black.}) 10. Nb5 Nb6 11. Nxa7+ Kd7 12. Nf3 f6 13. Nb5 Ra8 14. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gf4g3,Gf3d2] White will enjoy a small, but long-lasting advantage.} *

