{[%evp 0,22,24,24,24,-4,6,-4,46,26,25,29,23,34,53,39,61,61,49,50,50,26,37,35,35] [#]} 14. b4 $1 {I believe this is what Xiangzhi had in his preparation when he entered the Tarrasch again against Bai. The fire starts, and Black needs to be careful to survive!} cxb4 (14... g4 15. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. Nb5 a6 18. bxc5 $36 {[%cal Gc5c6] }) 15. Nb5 Qe7 (15... a6 16. Rxc6 $18) 16. Ne5 Rc8 17. e4 $3 {An amazing move! Our light-squared bishop is definitely eager to join the action!} a6 (17... dxe4 18. Bxe4 $18) 18. Nxc6+ bxc6 (18... Rxc6 19. Rxc6 bxc6 20. Nc3 Qb7 21. Rb1 $36 {}) 19. Nc3 Qb7 $1 {A strong move, but also purely defensive. For now, the queen is keeping everything together.} (19... bxc3 $4 20. Rxc3 $18 {[%cal Gf1b1]}) 20. a3 $36 {[%csl Rb8] The position looks very pleasant for White. With 14.b4!, we have a new position, and Black must have strong nerves to survive in a position with the exposed king on b8.} (20. Rb1 dxe4 21. Nxe4 Qb5 22. Qc2 {[%cal Gf1c1,Ge4c5,Gg2f1] is a good alternative for White.}) *

